<FIRST>u a AM-China-Defections 1stLd-Writethru a0566 06-11 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Defections, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0566,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Chinese Diplomats Announce Defection At Rally</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with confirmation from the FBI, men taken
to FBI office and requesting asylum, details of rally, quote from one defector;
ADDS byline. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY McGRATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men identified as Chinese Consulate
diplomats announced they can no longer support their government and
said they were defecting at a vigil on Saturday for students slain
in Beijing.
   To the amazement and delight of 5,000 people gathered in front of
City Hall, the duo mounted a stage and said that as Chinese
nationals and as human beings they could no longer go along with a
government whose troops fired on unarmed students.
   Both men were then taken to the nearby offices of the FBI, said a
policeman, Stanley Lee.
   They had called the bureau before the announcement, said K.K.
Woo, one of the rally organizers.
   The two announced their intention to request political asylum in
the United States, an FBI spokesman confirmed.
   A Chinese Consulate spokesman said he had not heard about the
men's statements and had no information.
   The men announced their action at a rally where a largely Asian
crowd, including some crying and many wearing black arm bands,
carried candles and makeshift banners reading ``Their blood, Our
tears.''
   The crowd cheered when the announcement was made, Woo said.
   Rally organizers, reading from the men's Chinese business cards,
identified the speakers as Zhou Li-ming and Chang Li-mun. But they
said they were unsure of the proper English transliteration.
   One of the diplomats told a local television station he was
optimistic about the future of the China's prodemocracy movement
despite the government's political crackdown.
   ``I think their victory is only temporary. The people will win,''
the man, who was not identified, told television station KTVU of
Oakland.
   The station said one of the men was the vice consul and the other
either the consulate's information officer or cultural affairs
officer.
   The FBI would release no information about the men.
</TEXT>
