<FIRST>u a AM-Hearns-Shooting 2ndLd-Writethru a0567 06-11 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hearns-Shooting, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0567,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Found Shot to Death in Boxer Thomas Hearns' Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with police confirmation of death, six people
being questioned, quotes from Las Vegas, other details. No pickup. Longer
version also moving on sports wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUSTIN BURKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOUTHFIELD, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman was shot to death in a bedroom
of boxer Thomas Hearns' home on Saturday night and six witnesses
were being questioned, police said.
   One of the boxer's brothers, accompanied by attorney Neil Fink,
was at the police station, but Southfield police Officer Gary Conat
refused to say whether Henry Hearns was among those being questioned.
   The woman, whose name was not released, was shot once in the
head, Conat said. She was in her 20s and known to the Hearns family,
he said. She was found about 9:40 p.m.
   Detectives found a gun they believed was used in the slaying,
said Conat.
   Hearns was in Las Vegas where he is to meet Sugar Ray Leonard on
Monday night in a scheduled 12-round fight for Leonard's World
Boxing Council super-middleweight title at Caesars Palace.
   ``He's going forward with the fight and he says it won't affect
him in the least,'' promoter Bob Arum said in Las Vegas. ``He did
assure me that the fight would go on and he said it wouldn't affect
his performance. Incidents are incidents and they're unfortunate,
but we're all professionals here.
   ``Is he concerned about his brother? He probably is, but he says
he doesn't want to think about it, and he won't.
   ``As he says, he'll block it out of his mind until he knocks Ray
Leonard out Monday night.''
   Arum said three people in Hearns' entourage left Las Vegas for
Detroit, including his younger brother, John Hearns, who is a
student at the University of Nevada-Las Vegas.
   His mother, Lois Hearns, will remain in Las Vegas for the fight.
``Tommy talked to her and asked her to stay in Las Vegas,'' Arum
said. ``She is here and she is going to stay.''
   Arum said ``it has been made clear to me that the (dead) woman
herself has absolutely no connection with Thomas.''
   Asked how he knew that since he didn't know the victim's name, he
said, ``They apparently know who she is.''
</TEXT>
