<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-89 0731EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i BC-Israel     06-11 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Israel,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Lifts Weeklong Curfew on Gaza Strip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE OLSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's military Sunday lifted a weeklong
curfew that confined 700,000 Palestinians to their homes in the Gaza
Strip, ending one of the longest restrictions imposed in the
18-month Arab uprising.
   Also Sunday, 15-year-old Mohammed Saeed Shaweeshin died of a
gunshot wound in the head suffered in a clash with soldiers Saturday
in Gaza's Jabaliya refugee camp, Arab reports said. An
eight-year-old boy also was killed in the stone-throwing
confrontation.
   Officials at Israel's Tel Hashomer Hospital near Tel Aviv, where
the teen-ager was taken for treatment, declined immediate comment.
The army said it is checking the report.
   Shaweeshin's death brings the toll to at least 515 Palestinians
killed since the revolt against Israeli rule began in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip. Twenty-two Israelis have died in the
violence.
   Some 4,000 cars carrying Palestinians left Gaza after the curfew
was lifted to take workers to their jobs in Israel, Israel Radio
said.
   But the restriction remained in Jabaliya camp, where 53,000
Palestinians had to stay home.
   The military imposed the curfew June 4 to control the population
by issuing identity cards that workers will have to show to enter
Israel.
   In the Tel Aviv suburb of Petah Tikva, 150 peace activists
demonstrated Sunday against the town's plan to require that Arab day
laborers wait in a specially designated ``transit station'' on the
outskirts.
   The activists say the plan, to keep Arabs out of the town center,
is racist.
   Police have challenging the legality of the station. Its planned
opening Sunday was delayed as town councilors debated.
   Eight Israeli peace activists who met with Palestine Liberation
Organization representatives in June 1987 were charged Sunday in an
Israeli court with violating anti-terror laws.
   Israel considers the PLO a terror organization and bans citizens
from meeting with the group.
   The activists were led by Charlie Biton, a Communist Party
legislator who was not charged because he has parliamentary immunity.
   If convicted, activists could be jailed for up to three years.
</TEXT>
