<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-89 1123EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     06-11 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Piedmont Flight 1253 to New York City was
delayed for more than an hour, but the reason wasn't a mechanical
problem, bad weather or labor strife _ it was a harmless 4-foot
snake.
   The plane was taxing out to take off from Baltimore-Washington
International Airport when a passenger saw the serpent slithering
down the aisle and alerted a flight attendant, said Larry Pickett,
spokesman for USAir, Piedmont's parent company.
   ``The pilot pulled back to the gate and all the passengers
deplaned, the maintenance people did their thing and the plane took
off about an hour later,'' Pickett said.
   Workers had to remove three seats in order to capture the
critter, a harmless gopher snake, Pickett said. Airline officials
did not know how it got into the plane, he said.
   The reptile was sent to a pet store.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHUA, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nancy Brehm said she and her daughter and
grandson were upstairs in their house one recent afternoon when they
heard an odd noise in the living room.
   About 12,000 bees, apparently swarming or looking for a new hive,
had flown down the chimney and tried to take up residence in the
Brehm house.
   Mrs. Brehm made a beeline for the upstairs telephone and called
her husband, Bruce, at work.
   ``I know my wife and daughter don't like insects, so I thought
they were exaggerating,'' Brehm said. ``I expected 10 or 20 bees. I
couldn't believe what I saw when I got there.''
   Mrs. Brehm said she called various agencies, including police and
exterminators, but no one would help. She finally persuaded
Peterborough beekeeper John Camp to come to her aid.
   Camp arrived with a beehive, about the same time the fire
department showed up to help the family out a second-floor window.
   Camp coaxed most of the bees into the hive, but a few were left
over.
   ``We were vacuuming bees til 1:30 in the morning and dead ones
are still turning up,'' Mrs. Brehm said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHATSWORTH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some residents of Murray County are seeing
red over what architects and an interior designer have done with
their new school.
   Kelly green is the school color at Murray County High, but parts
of the exterior of the new building are trimmed in turquoise.
   ``It's entirely different from the school color, more a sissy
green,'' said John Cochran, a junior.
   ``I just know it's not our color up there and I don't like it,''
said Melissa Headrick, who graduated from the high school 10 years
ago.
   But school board members decided last week to keep the turquoise
trim on the doors, roof edge and archways.
   Architect Jim Haigler, whose firm designed the building, said the
color was selected to blend with the building's main colors, beige
and white.
</TEXT>
