<DOCNO> AP890611-0011 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-89 1153EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HalfMoon     06-11 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Half Moon,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Replica Of Henry Hudson's Ship Christened At Albany Dock</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GERMAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly four centuries after explorer Henry
Hudson's crew mutinied and set him adrift, a replica of his ship has
been launched to honor the Netherlands' contributions to the New
World.
   ``What the sea separates, the shipbuilder unites,'' ship designer
Nicholas Benton told a crowd of about 500 Saturday before the
christening of the Half Moon.
   The 85-foot, 120-ton wooden vessel was lowered by crane into the
Hudson River, which Hudson discovered in 1609 during his search for
a Northwest passage to the Orient.
   Two years later, Hudson's crew mutinied, setting him, his young
son and seven others adrift in a small boat in Canada's Hudson Bay.
They were never seen again.
   The replica was conceived by Andrew Hendricks, a dermatologist
who plans to use the Half Moon as a platform to give history lessons
on Dutch contributions.
   Hudson himself was born in England but was working for the Dutch
East India Company at the time he found the river that bears his
name.
   There's a ``historical blind spot'' that keeps historians from
considering Dutch contributions to the New World, Hendricks said.
That's partly because the English ousted the Dutch from their early
stronghold in the New World in the 1600s, he said.
   The Dutch first settled the area between English colonies in
Virginia and New England, including Albany, the nation's oldest
incorporated city, he said.
   The ship will spend the summer touring the states once called the
New Netherlands _ New York, Connecticut, Pennsylvania, New Jersey
and Delaware.
   At the christening, Netherlands Consul General Adrien Tieleman
said the Dutch have always been proud of their ``small contribution
to the mightiest, most free and prosperous nation in the world.''
   The Half Moon replica cost about $1 million, raised mostly
through donations, and took a year to build. The builders are
applying finishing touches and the ship's maiden voyage is scheduled
for July 5.
   About 25 people worked to build the square-rigged ship, which
will be outfitted with replicas of 17th century cannons, said
shipwright Ernie Cowan of Mayville, N.Y.
   Sailmaker David Bierig of Erie, Pa., hand-sewed the ship's nine
sails. About 600 man-hours went into the sails, made of synthetics
treated to look like canvas sails of the 1600s, he said.
   Because ships four centuries ago were built for cargo, the squat
Half Moon won't win any races, Bierig said.
   ``It will be on the slow side,'' he said. ``Sailors were cheap
and in those days there was no reason you needed speed.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
