<FIRST>r a AM-HandcuffCaper     06-11 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Handcuff Caper,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspects Find Way to Shatter Shackles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inmates being driven from one jail to
another smilingly showed the officer guarding them their new
discovery: that their seat belts made handy tools for breaking
handcuffs.
   The sheriff's office and FBI didn't smile, though, and are
warning officers nationwide of the technique.
   ``There is danger to every law enforcement officer in the
country,'' said Franklin County Sheriff Earl O. Smith.
   Ten prisoners learned the seat belt trick while being taken from
the downtown jail to the Jackson Pike jail, and before the ride was
over all were free, Smith said Saturday.
   ``When the deputy opened the back of the van, all 10 guys were
smiling and said `See what we did,''' Smith said, adding that each
prisoner held up his arms to show broken handcuffs.
   The cuffs that go around each wrist are connected by a chain,
attached to each cuff by a swivel that moves freely to ensure that
the chain doesn't twist.
   Seat belt clips have one or two holes or slots, that lock them
into place with the buckle. The prisoners learned that jamming the
swivel link through a hole on the clip stops the swivel from turning
freely.
   ``A quick twist of the wrist, and the chain shears off at the
cuff,'' Smith said.
   The prank led Franklin County authorities to issue emergency
bulletins to law enforcement agencies across the state Friday.
Similar warnings also would be given nationwide, the sheriff said,
and an FBI spokesman said an advisory would be placed in the
agency's Law Enforcement Bulletin.
   ``Although only 10 people know the technique, I guarantee that
the entire jail population, all 690 of them, will know how to do it
before the day is up,'' Smith said. ``The only people who won't know
about it is law enforcement officers.''
   Smith ordered seat belts removed from jail vans. He also ordered
that prisoners in police cars be cuffed with their hands behind
their backs and that the seat belts be locked firmly across them.
   Handcuff manufacturers were contacted Friday and are studying
ways of redesigning the handcuffs, Smith said.
   The 10 inmates who revealed their discovery may regret the caper.
The sheriff was not amused.
   ``Charge them with destruction of county property,'' he told
deputies. ``We'll see how funny they think that is.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
