<DOCNO> AP890611-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-89 1242EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-HouseRaces Bjt   06-11 1115</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-House Races, Bjt,950</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Bucks Likely to Characterize Races for Pepper, Wright, Coelho
Seats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millions of dollars of special interest money
is expected to prime the political pumps as Republicans battle for
three historically Democratic seats in races spawned by the
congressional ethics wars and the death of Claude Pepper.
   ``You're going to see candidates in all of these races spending a
good deal of time trying to squeeze money out of the lobbyists, and
there's no doubt that millions of dollars special interest funds
will pour in,'' says Michael Waldman of Congress Watch, a citizens
group based here.
   The stakes are not momentous, since Democrats control the House,
259 to 175, and even a Republican sweep would not change things
much. For that matter, registered Democrats predominate in all three
districts.
   But Republicans lost face in April with special-election defeats
in Alabama and Indiana, even though they held on in Wyoming. They
want to avenge those losses in the upcoming round. Democrats, on the
other hand, want to avoid the embarrassment of an upset.
   The three districts are:
   _The 12th District of Texas, taking in much of Fort Worth. Jim
Wright, who has represented it since 1955, stepped down as House
Speaker on May 31 at the end of a yearlong ethics probe and is
expected to resign from the House itself by the end of the month.
   _The 15th District of California, in the rich cotton, fruit and
vegetable-growing San Joaquin Valley, the nation's premier center of
agribusiness. House Majority Whip Tony Coelho, who represented the
district since 1979, announced on May 27 that he would resign to
head off a protracted controversy over a $100,000 ``junk bond''
purchase.
   _The 18th District of Florida, taking in much of Miami, Miami
Beach, Key Biscayne and Coral Gables. Rules Chairman Claude Pepper
died May 30 after representing the district since 1962.
   There is no denying that the races will cost a bundle.
   ``We're talking about $500,000 at this point, but if we have to
go higher, I guess we can,'' says Modesto, Calif., Mayor Carole
Whiteside, already an announced candidate. ``But I want to earn this
race, I don't want to buy it.''
   Candidates in April's Indiana race spent $500,000 each as did
contestants in a Wyoming election where Republicans eked out victory
on April 29. Need for money and lack of time most likely will send
the new set of candidates scurrying to Washington lobbies that have
plenty of ready cash as well as long legislative shopping lists.
   ``I would think that the Democrats would do what they've done
already, which is to organize labor union political action
committees to turn on the spigot, and Republicans will do what we
can to reach out to the business PACs to help raise money for
Republicans,'' says John Buckley, spokesman for the National
Republican Congressional Committee.
   In Texas, Senate Finance Committee Chairman Lloyd Bentsen already
is putting out word that he backs Fort Worth attorney Pete Geren.
   Geren, 37, a former Bentsen staffer, is unlikely to announce,
however, until after Wright leaves or at least sets a specific date
for his departure. Other Democrats being mentioned as possible
contenders include state Sen. Hugh Parmer and former state Rep. Mike
Millsap as well as Fort Worth Councilman Gary Gilley.
   Republicans include state Rep. Billy Carter, television health
show host Dr. Bob Lanier, airport board member Erma Johnson, former
Republican county Chairman Jim Ryan and county Judge Roy English,
who switched to the GOP at a heavily ballyhooed White House ceremony
in 1986.
   Under Texas law, candidates from both parties slug it out in a
single special election, with a runoff between the two top vote
getters if no one gains a majority.
   In California, Democratic state Rep. Gary Condit is also
campaigning.
   Condit, 41, is a member of the ``Gang of Five,'' conservative
Democrats who warred with liberal Assembly Speaker Willie Brown in
1988. ``I was stripped of all my committee assignments and had my
office moved about once a month,'' Condit chortles.
   The antics helped Condit. ``Fighting with Willie Brown didn't
hurt him at all because fighting with a liberal in that district is
what you want to do,'' says GOP consultant George Gorton of San
Diego.
   Water availability and quality loom as crucial issues in
district, where farmers are also irked by pollution damage to crops
from autos of increasingly numerous commuters to Bay Area jobs. Both
candidates vow to shun negative campaigning.
   Whiteside does say, however, that ``my opponent already has been
involved in special interest politics in Sacramento and Sacramento,
frankly, is not a whole lot better than Washington. I'm glad I
wasn't there.''
   Only one other Democrat has been mentioned as a possible
contender: state Rep. Rusty Areias, D-Los Banos, another ``Gang of
Five'' member. Republicans include Stanislaus County Chairman
Barbara Keating-Edh, Fresno County Supervisor Daran Koligian, Fresno
Councilman Rod Anaforian, Merced businessman Terry Newman and highly
decorated Vietnam veteran Chris Patterakis.
   Under California law, candidates of both parties are lumped in
one race. If no one gains a majority, the top Republican fights the
leading Democrat in a runoff.
   The Florida election, set for Aug. 29, puts the spotlight on the
sizeable Cuban-American community in the Miami area.
   Pepper won their hearts with TV ads in Spanish and firm backing
for Nicaragua's Contra rebels while cementing ties with just about
every other ethnic group in one way or another. In 1988, the
88-year-old lawmaker ran without opposition.
   Battle lines are drawn again, however, with two Cuban-Americans
already in the race on the Republican side, state Sen. Ileana
Ros-Lehtinen and millionaire banana importer Carlos Perez, a
prominent supporter of former President Reagan and Lt. Col. Oliver
North.
   Among Democrats, state Sen. Jack Gordon, a one-time Claude Pepper
business partner who plans to get in the race this week,
acknowledges that his stand against Contra aid could be vexing. ``As
a matter of fact, the right-wing Cubans threw rocks and eggs at me''
at an anti-Contra demonstration, he says. He says he has a strategy
to counteract the problem that he will reveal this week.
   ``I think the chances are pretty good for a Cuban-American to be
elected,'' said Democratic strategist Sergio Bendixen.
   Already announced among Republicans are state Sen. Ileana
Ros-Lehtinen and millionaire banana importer Carlos Perez, a
high-profile supporter of former President Reagan and Lt. Col.
Oliver North.
   Also mentioned as a possible contenders was GOP state Sen. Al
Gutman. Democrats include Hialeah Mayor Raul Martinez Commissioner
Rosario Kennedy, Miami Beach Mayor Alex Daoud, Dade County
Commissioner Joe Gersten, State Attorney Janet Reno and former
school board chairman Paul Cejas.
</TEXT>
