<FIRST>r w AM-Honecker     06-11 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honecker,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>East German Welcomes Bush Arms Plan, Cites New Berlin Wall Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the East German government says
President Bush's proposal for a reduction in conventional arms in
Europe is a welcome step that is in tune with Warsaw Pact desires
for speedy negotiations, according to a published report.
   The Washington Post also quoted Erich Honecker in its Sunday
edition as confirming that East German border guards have been
ordered not to use deadly force to stop civilians who attempt to
flee into West Germany unless the soldiers are threatened themselves.
   In a two-hour interview conducted last Wednesday in East Berlin,
the Post quoted the influential Warsaw Pact leader as saying the
Bush proposal for NATO and Warsaw Pact nations to cut conventional
arms is ``close to our striving for radical conventional
disarmament.''
   Questioned on Bush's call to ``lock in'' reductions in tanks,
artillery, armed personnel carriers and other non-nuclear forces in
Vienna during a 23-nation negotiation on Conventional Forces in
Europe, the paper quoted Honecker as replying:
   ``We are interested in having those proposals included in the
negotiations, so that we can identify where the Warsaw Treaty states
concur (with NATO) and those areas where more intensive negotiations
are needed.''
   As to nuclear arms, he said, ``We are in favor of the
step-by-step elimination of tactical nuclear weapons in Europe. Of
course we know that this can't be done in one stroke.'' He raised
the possibility that each side might decide to ``keep, say, 10''
weapons.
   ``One has to enter negotiations and see what progress can be
achieved,'' said Honecker, who is head of state and general
secretary of the East German Communist Party. ``Sometimes surprises
even occur.''
   He rejected Bush's call for the Berlin Wall to be torn down, but
said his government wants ``to humanize the border regime'' as part
of generally improving relations with Western Europe and the United
States.
   Honecker said East German border guards are authorized to shoot
people trying to flee the country only if the guards are in physical
danger or if a soldier or other uniformed person is trying to desert.
   He did not say when the restrictions took effect, but Western
officials have said the policy apparently was adopted as a goodwill
gesture prior to Honecker's visit to West Germany in 1987.
   Although 190 people have died trying to flee East Germany since
the wall was built in 1961, there has been only one confirmed case
since the 1987 Honecker visit to West Berlin.
</TEXT>
