<FIRST>d w AM-HurricaneHotline     06-11 0149</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hurricane Hotline,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hurricane Hotline Resumes</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release at 6:30 p.m. EDT, time set by source</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ``Hurricane Hotline'' will resume this year
when a storm threatens, the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration announced Sunday.
   The hotline is a special telephone service providing regular
updates of the progress of named tropical storms and hurricanes. It
operates only when such a storm is active.
   Last year the hotline received more than 100,000 calls during
Hurricane Gilbert, and the year before 700,000 calls were recorded
when hurricanes Gloria and Elena threatened, officials said.
   The hotline number is 1-900-410-NOAA and calls cost 50 cents for
the first minute and 45 cents for each additional minute. Most calls
cost 95 cents, officials say.
   The hotline, which has a taped message, is operated by the
National Hurricane Center in Coral Gables, Fla., with assistance
from NBC News and USA Today.
</TEXT>
