<FIRST>u i AM-China-Dissidents     06-11 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Dissidents,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Zeroes in on Prominent Dissidents</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has moved to silence three top
dissidents who share a passion for democracy: an internationally
known astrophysicist, his college professor wife and a shaggy-haired
accountant.
   The Public Security Department issued an arrest warrant for
astrophysicist Fang Lizhi and his wife, Li Shuxian, who are hiding
in the U.S. Embassy in Beijing.
   Meanwhile, ABC News quoted Chinese sources as saying another
dissident, Ren Wanding, was arrested late Saturday.
   Fang, 53, is the most prominent dissident in China. He was
expelled from the Communist Party in 1987 on charges of having
helped provoke an earlier series of student pro-democracy
demonstrations.
   After his expulsion, Fang continued to condemn Marxism as a
failure and to urge democratic change in this authoritarian
Communist state. He also sent an open letter to Deng Xiaoping in
January calling for the release of political prisoners.
   ``Many people don't agree with Marxism, even workers and
students,'' he said in an interview with The Associated Press last
year. ``Even people of my generation ... don't believe in Marxism.''
   The Beijing Observatory professor was at the center of a
U.S.-Chinese controversy in February when Chinese police prevented
him from attending a banquet given by visiting U.S. President George
Bush.
   Although he kept a low profile during the recent student-led
demonstrations for democracy, Fang told The Associated Press just
before he disappeared into the U.S. Embassy that he feared he would
be arrested as part of a crackdown on liberal intellectuals.
   His wife is a professor of physics at Beijing University, the
country's most prestigious school, and also has criticized the lack
of democracy in China.
   She was elected a deputy to the People's Congress of Beijing's
Haidian district by Beijing University students.
   Ren Wanding does not have the international standing enjoyed by
Fang but nonetheless has waged a crusade for human rights and
democracy in China.
   Ren, 44, was jailed in 1979-83 after helping edit an underground
pro-democracy magazine. After a long silence, he renewed his call
for multi-party democracy late last year with an open letter to the
U.N. Human Rights Commission and a 22-page essay on freedom.
   After the recent pro-democracy movement began, he went to
universities and student-occupied Tiananmen Square to read his
essays on political reform. But Ren insisted he had no formal
connection with the student protesters.
   At a news conference two week ago, Ren told reporters he feared
arrest but defended his actions and speeches. ``I must speak,'' he
said. ``It is my fate to do such things.''
</TEXT>
