<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-89 1357EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-PhoneTalks     06-11 0751</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Phone Talks,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>AT&amp;T Pact In Hand, Unions Open Talks With Baby Bells</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two unions and the seven so-called Baby Bells
spawned by the 1984 AT&amp;T breakup begin contract talks this month, a
splintered and complex process affecting more than 350,000 workers
in 48 states and the District of Columbia.
   Across the tables from unions at negotiations in seven cities
will be representatives from the highly profitable regional phone
companies, several of which were hit by strikes three years ago in
their first post-divestiture negotiations.
   ``Both sides had problems in 1986,'' Communications Workers of
America President Morton Bahr said in an interview last week.
``There was no blueprint. There were people involved who had never
negotiated a contract before.''
   The unions, CWA and the International Brotherhood of Electrical
Workers, say the blueprint for this year's talks is the recent
agreement they reached with American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co.,
which includes wage and pension increases, a profit-sharing plan and
an innovative package of benefits dealing with parental and elder
care leaves and child care.
   Spokesmen for the regional phone companies, however, say they do
not feel obligated to match the AT&amp;T contract.
   ``We'd be reluctant to acknowledge that any patterns have been
set,'' said NYNEX spokesman Robert O'Brien. ``Things will vary from
one region of the country to another and I don't think we want to be
locked into any feeling that a pattern has been set. We want to
start at the beginning.''
   Added BellSouth's Terry Johnson: ``We are different companies
facing different circumstances and what AT&amp;T and the CWA doe is
between that company and those union members. Ours is a completely
different situation as far as we are concerned.''
   Nonetheless, AT&amp;T briefed officials representing all of the
regional companies last week.
   For NYNEX, parent company for the local phone service providers
in New York and most of New England, the beginning of the talks is
Tuesday, the same day the unions first sit down for formal
negotiations with US West, which provides service to 14 states in
the Midwest and West, and Pacific Telesis, which serves Nevada and
California.
   Talks between the unions and two of the companies begin Monday.
They are Ameritech, parent company of local phone companies in
Indiana, Michigan, Ohio and Wisconsin; and BellSouth, which serves
nine southeastern states.
   Negotiations with Bell Atlantic, which serves six Mid-Atlantic
states and the District of Columbia, open on June 19 and the final
Baby Bell, Southwestern Bell, which serves Arkansas, Kansas,
Missouri, Oklahoma and Texas, will open formal negotiations June 26.
   Four of the contracts expire Aug. 5; the others Aug. 12, except
for Ameritech's Illinois Bell, which faces a July 1 deadline and has
already begun negotiations.
   Parts of NYNEX, US West and Ameritech were struck in 1986. Bahr
said the unions were making preparations for strikes this year as
well but said he was optimistic settlements would be reached by the
deadlines.
   CWA represents all but 32,000 of the 352,000 union workers at the
seven companies, with IBEW representing the others.
   The unions have a nationwide agenda that will dominate all of the
talks, but there are a number of local issues as well.
   The national issues will mirror those in the AT&amp;T talks, with
health insurance again likely to emerge as the major hurdle to
settlements.
   Bahr identified NYNEX and Pacific Telesis as the companies with
which he expected the greatest fight over health insurance.
Ameritech, BellSouth and Southwestern Bell already have in place
many of the cost-containment measures that were inserted into the
recent AT&amp;T agreement.
   The unions also want all of the companies to offer profit
sharing; some now offer performance-related bonuses but the unions
say they are inadequate.
   Another provision of the AT&amp;T contract the unions will be seeking
in the regional talks is company participation in a lobbying effort
designed to curb rising health care costs through revisions in
federal policy.
   Bahr said he was optimistic the companies would sign on, but said
the larger problem will be getting them, major employers from other
industries, lawmakers and interest groups to reach consensus on a
strategy.
   As for local issues, disputes over job titles and use of outside
contracts likely will surface at all of the regional talks. NYNEX is
the only one of the Baby Bells still offering cost of living
adjustments to its workers and any attempt by the company to
eliminate those would be meet heavy resistance from union
negotiators.
</TEXT>
