<FIRST>r a AM-China-Defections 1stLd-Writethru a0592 06-11 0738</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Defections, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0592,0754</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Chinese Diplomats Defect at San Francisco Rally</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 12th graf, `In Washington...', to UPDATE with no-comment
from State Department.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of protesters and even some police
officers wept as two Chinese diplomats made a surprise and emotional
public appeal for political asylum, and rally organizers Sunday
predicted more defections.
   ``Many of my friends have lost their lives and we wanted to do
something to show we support what they stood for,'' said one of the
diplomats during a rally Saturday night against China's repression
of the pro-democracy movement.
   ``Compared to them, I am not brave at all,'' added the man, who
was not immediately identified. ``They are brave for standing up for
democracy in the face of death or imprisonment.''
   The two men, identified as a vice consul for cultural affairs and
an overseas affairs officer, told the crowd of 5,000 they decided to
defect after Beijing leaders launched a propaganda campaign claiming
no citizens died in the clash.
   Chinese troops opened fire on tens of thousands of students and
Beijing residents June 4 to put an end to the seven-week
pro-democracy movement and the sit-in at the city's Tiananmen
Square. U.S. intelligence estimates put the number of people slain
in the hundreds and possibly the thousands.
   ``We are supposed to tell you that no one was injured or killed.
Why? Because we are diplomats. But we won't fake it here. Before we
are diplomats, we are Chinese and we are human beings,'' one of the
men told the crowd.
   ``We are public servants, we are not slaves,'' he added.
   The whereabouts of the diplomats Sunday were not immediately
known.
   The FBI would not release their names but confirmed the two
requested political asylum. A bureau spokeswoman Sunday said only
that their case would be handled by the Immigration and
Naturalization Service.
   A staffer in the office of David Ilchert, INS regional director,
said Sunday morning the two had not filed an asylum request. He
would not give his name.
   To obtain political asylum, an applicant must show a well-founded
fear of persecution in their homeland.
   In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Daria Novak said the
department had no immediate comment on the situation.
   Telephone calls to the Chinese consulate went unanswered.
   Organizers at the rally and candlelight memorial said at first
they refused to allow the consulate officials to address the crowd
outside City Hall. Even later, when event organizers were convinced
of their sincerity, three people were posted alongside the diplomats
on stage to yank them off in case of trouble.
   ``We didn't know if they'd start a riot or what, and it was a
complete surprise for everyone when they said what they did,'' said
Humphrey Wou, a member of the Chinese Christian Mission, one of the
sponsors of the rally.
   ``But then we were ecstatic and everybody was hugging them and
crying and saying that they were true Chinese and very, very
brave,'' Wou said. He said he saw several police officers weeping
after the announcement.
   Wou and other rally organizers predicted there would be other
defections from Chinese consulates in the United States.
   ``We are encouraging this sort of thing to happen and expect more
people to come out of these consulates to freedom,'' said Steve Lu,
general coordinator of San Francisco-based Support Democracy in
China. However, Wou said he expects most Chinese students eventually
to return home to support the pro-democracy cause.
   Lee Man-kar, an editor at San Francisco's Chinese Times, on
Sunday identified the two from their business cards as Zhou Li-ming,
26, vice consul for cultural affairs, and Zhang Li-man, 25, acting
consul for overseas affairs. He said both had been in the United
States for 2{ years and were unmarried.
   He estimated that the total number of Chinese staff members and
dependents at the consulate was 300 to 400.
   Wou said the diplomats told him they had walked to the rally
after finishing dinner at the Chinese Consulate, about a half-mile
away. On the way, they stopped at a public telephone and called the
FBI, which escorted them to an undisclosed location from the rally.
   The defections were announced in Chinese and English at the
protest, where a largely Asian crowd denounced the Beijing
government. Many wore black arm bands and carried banners reading
``Their blood, Our tears.''
</TEXT>
