<FIRST>r i AM-France-NuclearTest     06-11 0146</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Nuclear Test,0150</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Zealand Detects French Nuclear Test</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France detonated its fourth
underground nuclear bomb this year in the South Pacific, New Zealand
government scientists said Sunday.
   The explosion of about 70 kilotons occurred Saturday at Fangatau
atoll in French Polynesia, said Warwick Smith of the Department of
Industrial and Scientific Research.
   It brings to 107 the number of underground tests Paris has
conducted since it began nuclear tests in the region in 1975, Smith
said.
   This year the French exploded an 11-kiloton bomb on May 11, a
two-kiloton bomb on May 20 and one of 20 kilotons on June 4. One
kiloton is equivalent to blasting 1,000 tons of TNT.
   New Zealand and other South Pacific nations question the safety
of the tests and argue they escalate the arms race.
   France refuses to confirm reports of nuclear testing.
</TEXT>
