<FIRST>r a AM-People     06-11 1007</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,1046</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After industrialist Armand Hammer decided not
to give his $250 million art collection to the Los Angeles County
Museum of Art, its trustees decided they don't want the 21-year
member on the board anymore.
   Hammer's term will expire June 30, following the board's refusal
last week to renew Hammer's trusteeship, said Museum board president
Daniel Belin. The chairman of Occidental Petroleum Corp. has been a
board member since 1968.
   Hammer, 91, dashed expectations in January 1988 by announcing he
would not be donating his collection of Old Master and 19th century
paintings to the museum. He had insisted that his collection be
housed in its own wing, separate from the museum's existing
collection and overseen by a separate curator, Belin and others said.
   ``That was unacceptable,'' Belin said.
   Hammer subsequently decided to house his art in a private museum
to be built in Westwood for at least $86 million. Several Occidental
shareholders have filed a lawsuit trying to block the plan, claiming
it is a waste of corporate assets without significant benefit to the
company.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Clint Eastwood said Sunday that he
hoped his first African film venture will encourage the conservation
of wild animals, particularly the African elephant.
   The movie will criticize the obsessional hunting of big game
animals for ivory or souvenirs, Eastwood said.
   ``I think it is better in the long run run to have animals alive
than dead trinkets,'' he said. ``I personally will not buy ivory for
this reason.''
   Eastwood arrived in Zimbabwe from France late Saturday and was
scheduled to travel 240 miles to the remote town of Kariba to begin
filming ``White Hunter, Black Heart'' on Tuesday.
   He is producer, director and star of the movie based on Peter
Viertel's novel set in Africa during the filming of director John
Huston's classic ``The African Queen.''
   Marco Barla, spokesman for Eastwood's Malpaso production company,
said the movie depicts the obsession of fictional movie director
John Wilson, based on Huston, with the African bush and his desire
to kill an elephant in its bush habitat.
   ``We are making an anti-hunting statement,'' Barla said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Goldie Hawn will start building her
country-style mansion in Pacific Palisades after more than a year of
planning.
   Construction of the 10,000 square-foot residence in the coastal
suburb, 20 miles west of downtown Los Angeles, will take about 15
months.
   Miss Hawn, star of such films as ``Cactus Flower'' and ``Private
Benjamin,'' paid $2.1 million in April 1988 for the property, and
then demolished the existing house, according to Readysystems Group
in Burbank.
   She is currently in Canada filming ``Bird on a Wire'' with
co-star Mel Gibson.

</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: Ms. Holliday is cq as second reference to Russell Holiday.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MYRTLE BEACH, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   During a visit to Myrtle Beach, Oliver
North was just like any other tourist.
   The retired Marine colonel took a spin at amusement-park rides,
went to see the new Indiana Jones movie and caught King mackerel
while deep-sea fishing here last week.
   ``People would ask him if he was going to run for president,''
said Russell Holliday, co-owner of the beach house where North and
his family stayed. ``He would laugh and say right now he was real
busy running for husband and father.''
   ``He said this was the most relaxed he has been in many, many
months,'' Ms. Holliday said. ``They needed to get away. They had a
normal vacation. They sat on the beach, and they had suntans. They
had a great time despite the weather.''
   His wife Betsy, two of their children and a security guard
accompanied North.
   A federal court recently found North guilty of three of 12 felony
counts for his role in the Iran-Contra affair. Sentencing has been
set for June 23.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If Judge Joseph A. Wapner of television's ``The
People's Court'' wants to hear small claims cases in this historic
city, court officials say he can go right ahead and help himself.
   The television show, which features the retired judge arbitrating
real disputes in California, is on the road this year taping the
courtroom show in other cities.
   Producer Jim Crum approached Chief Justice William J. Tierney of
the Municipal Court about opening up small claims files to the
show's researchers and a courtroom to the show's star.
   Tierney, in a recent letter to Crum, said the court would be
pleased to cooperate.
   The old Suffolk County courthouse, where the Boston Municipal
Court's small claims section is located, was built 103 years ago and
is listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
   After researchers find some interesting suits, Crum said, the
litigants would be contacted to see whether they want to have Wapner
settle their claims, instead of pursuing them in the real courts.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RAPID CITY, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Filming of ``Dances With Wolves,''
starring Kevin Costner, is set to begin July 17, according to a
South Dakota stockbroker who said he persuaded the film company to
come here instead of Nebraska.
   The movie, which will be Costner's debut as a director, is to be
shot primarily near Fort Pierre and north of Rapid City along the
Belle Fourche River, said Guy Edwards.
   Edwards helped persuade Costner and the movie's producers to film
in the Rapid City area instead of going to Valentine, Neb., where
most of the film was to have been shot. He has since helped the
actor and the film company prepare for two months of shooting in
western South Dakota.
   ``Costner will visit Rapid City one more time sometime next week
to finalize a few things,'' Edwards said last week. ``He'll be here
a day or two before heading to Pierre to finish up things there
before shooting begins.''
   The movie takes place in 1863 and revolves around the character
played by Costner, Lt. John Dunbar, and his experiences with members
of a plains Indian tribe.
   Costner's most recent movie is ``Field of Dreams.''
