<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-89 1453EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MosaicsTrial     06-11 0746</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mosaics Trial,0771</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mosaics Verdict Rests on Two Legal Issues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JODI PERRAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an odd way, Indianapolis art dealer Peg
Goldberg feels honored.
   ``Very few people in the United States have had the privilege of
being sued not only by a country, but by a religion,'' Goldberg said
following the conclusion of a six-day civil trial in U.S. District
Court last week.
   The Republic of Cyprus and the Autocephalous Greek Orthodox
Church of Cyprus are demanding the return of four sixth-century
Christian mosaics. Taken from a church in northern Cyprus in 1979,
the works were purchased by Goldberg last summer.
   Goldberg says she fell in love with the rare Byzantine pieces and
purchased them for $1.1 million only after her investigation turned
up no evidence they had been reported stolen. She later offered them
for sale for $20 million, but they are off the market pending the
outcome of the lawsuit.
   Judge James E. Noland's decision, which is not expected until
August at the earliest, could rest on two legal questions:
   _Did Goldberg act recklessly and hastily when she purchased the
mosaics during a four-day visit to Switzerland in July?
   _Did Cyprus diligently seek the return of the mosaics and try to
notify the international art community after it learned the works
were stolen in 1979?
   At stake are not only the ``spiritual treasures'' of one of the
earliest Christian religions, but also the status of antiquities in
United States museums and around the world, analysts say.
   Goldberg's actions were criticized in testimony from three
witnesses: a Harvard University law professor and curators at the J.
Paul Getty Museum in Malibu, Calif., and Walters Art Gallery in
Baltimore, Md.
   Gary Vikan of the Baltimore gallery said the objects,
circumstances and people involved in Goldberg's purchase should have
warned her away.
   Among those who brought Goldberg into the deal were an
Indianapolis art dealer who has used three names and a Dutchman who
has been convicted of art forgery in France, court records show.
   The Dutchman, Michel van Rijn, is well-known as a ``shady
dealer'' who markets stolen art, Vikan testified. But Goldberg
testified she liked van Rijn and he seemed to have universal respect
in Amsterdam.
   ``There wasn't anyplace that we went that somebody didn't come
out of a shop and say, `Hi, Michel,''' she said. ``We were always
bumping into people he would chat with and introduce me to.''
   The roughly 2-foot-square mosaics _ which depict the heads of
Jesus as a boy, the apostles James and Matthew and an archangel _
were taken from a war-torn area of northern Cyprus under control of
a breakaway Turkish state recognized only by Turkey.
   Vikan testified he would have walked away from the purchase.
   New York art dealer Andre Emmerich, a former president of the Art
Dealers Association of America, said he might have gone ahead.
   ``When confronted by a really major work of art, and it's
perfectly clear the piece is authentic and of unequaled quality, I
might well have proceeded the same way. My God, yes,'' Emmerich
testified on Goldberg's behalf.
   Emmerich also testified he felt Goldberg had left ``no stone
unturned'' in her investigation.
   ``I think her inquiry met the best professional standards,''
Emmerich said. ``I couldn't have expected more.''
   Goldberg seemed incredulous at the suggestion she would sacrifice
her business and the livelihood of her partner, George Feldman, by
purchasing stolen artwork.
   ``Who in their right mind can imagine that we would borrow one
million dollars to buy stolen property?'' she said.
   Goldberg's attorneys tried to prove Cyprus gave up claim to the
mosaics when Greek Cypriots fled the village of Lythrankomi in 1976,
leaving the church and its mosaics unattended. Turkish forces had
taken control of the area, stifling the rights of Greek citizens,
Greek Cypriots testified.
   ``Did, in fact, southern Cyprus have a right to lay claim to
something in northern Cyprus?'' Goldberg asked.
   Six Greek Cypriot officials testified how they tried to recover
the mosaics against political and bureaucratic roadblocks erected by
the division of their country.
   They said they notified museums and agencies of the theft, issued
press releases and sent representatives to speak about stolen
Cypriot antiquities at international art conferences.
   However, none of them could say they had notified Interpol, an
international police agency, or tried to pursue Aydin Dikmen, the
Turk who sold the mosaics to Goldberg and who had been publicly
linked to the mosaics in 1982.
</TEXT>
