<FIRST>r w AM-ViolentCrime     06-11 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Violent Crime,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>One in Four U.S. Households Hit by Crime Last Year, Survey Finds</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release at 6 p.m. EDT, time set by source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of every four U.S. households was the
target of a violent crime or theft in 1988, the same proportion as
the previous three years, the Justice Department said Sunday.
   This proportion remained at the lowest level since the Bureau of
Justice Statistics began calculating the household rate in 1975.
That year, almost one in three households was the target of a
violent crime.
   ``In 1988, 27 percent of households with incomes of $25,000 or
more, 29 percent of black households and 30 percent of urban
households were touched by crime,'' the report found, adding that
Hispanic households remained more vulnerable to crime than
non-Hispanic households.
   Geographically, households in the Northeast were the least
vulnerable to crime, with 19 percent hit, while those in the West
suffered the most with 30.3 percent. About 24.9 percent of
Midwestern households and 24.4 percent of Southern households were
hit, the report found.
   The report, based on the National Crime Survey, covered 92.9
million households and found that 22.8 million experienced a theft
or burglary or had a member who was raped, robbed or assaulted.
   The Bureau of Justice Statistics does not include murders in the
survey because it relies on a polling technique based on what the
crime victim says and then estimates a total amount of crime
nationwide.
   Murder statistics would not change the overall figures for
household crimes, the bureau said. Other crimes not measured by the
crime survey include kidnapping and arson.
   Overall, members of about 141,000 households were raped, 872,000
were robbed and 3.7 million were assaulted, and the bureau found a
total of 7.19 million households, or one in 13, were targeted by
crimes of ``high concern,'' including rape, robbery, assault by a
stranger or a burglar.
   Black households, 29 percent of which were touched by crime, were
significantly more vulnerable to crime than white households, of
which 23.9 percent were targeted, the bureau found.
   In addition, black households were more likely than white
households, if victimized, to be victimized by a serious violent
crime or a crime of high concern, the report said.
   A total of 16 percent of the black households touched by crime in
1988 had a member suffer a rape, robbery or aggravated assault,
while 9 percent of white households had a member who suffered from
one of those crimes, according to the study.
   The bureau, in trying to explain the overall downward trend in
the households-touched-by-crime indicator since 1975, said
``population movements and changes in household composition
undoubtedly affected'' it.
   In addition to a movement away from the Northeast and Midwest in
the South and West as well as away from urban areas into suburban
and rural areas, the report noted that the average American
household decreased in size during the 1975-88 period.
   ``One-person households represented 21 percent of all households
in 1975 but 25 percent in 1988,'' which the percentage of households
containing six or more people fell from 7 percent to 3 percent, the
report said.
   If a household contains more people, it is more vulnerable to
crime, particularly for personal crimes since larger households have
more members at risk, the study said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890611-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-89 1508EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina     06-11 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agreement Seems Near on Early Exit for Alfonsin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Carlos Menem will
assume power several months ahead of schedule in an agreement being
worked out with Argentina's lame-duck leader, Raul Alfonsin,
officials said Sunday.
   The arrangement would allow Menem to begin tackling the nation's
crippling economic problems sometime this summer, rather than wait
until December, when he is scheduled to take over from President
Alfonsin.
   ``I have no doubt he doesn't want to stay until Dec. 10,'' Juan
Manuel Casella, an official of the governing Radical Civic Union,
said of Alfonsin. ``There will be an accord shortly.''
   Casella was the governing party candidate for vice president in
the May 14 elections, which were won by Menem of the Peronist Party.
   Under the constitution, Menem is scheduled to take office on Dec.
10.
   But with the economy in chaos and food riots in early June that
left 14 dead, many people have called on Alfonsin to step aside
sooner.
   Although no date was set in weekend talks between the two main
parties, Alfonsin might hand over power in the first half of August,
said Eduardo Menem, the senate president and a key adviser to his
older brother.
   President-elect Menem has said he won't push Alfonsin to step
down early. But last week, after he appointed a Cabinet and fleshed
out an economic plan, the Peronist said he was prepared to take
power any time.
   Shortly after the Peronist election landslide, Alfonsin offered
to step down early, but he could not agree with Menem on terms. The
main differences were over economic policies and how Alfonsin could
leave office without resigning.
   Menem also insisted that Peronist congressmen who won election
with him take office when he does and that the trials of military
officers charged with human rights abuse during the 1976-83
dictatorship be resolved by Alfonsin.
   The military ``situation stems from the current government and I
consider it convenient that the answer and the solution be granted
by this government,'' Menem said.
   In an apparent solution worked out over the weekend, the
Electoral College would meet early to confirm Menem's victory and
Congress would modify the law that sets the transition day. That
would allow Alfonsin to step down without resigning.
   In addition, Radical Civic Union congressmen would agree to
support whatever legislation Menem deemed necessary to stabilize the
economy, which has soared out of control under Alfonsin.
   Hyperinflation, economic recession and high unemployment caused
food riots in which Argentines looted supermarkets and grocery
stores. Alfonsin declared a nationwide state of siege.
   Alfonsin has tried to cut the budget deficit _ a main cause of
inflation _ by cutting government spending and raising tariffs for
public services. The measures, coupled with inflation expected to
reach 70 percent this month, have torn into pocketbooks and prompted
cries for Alfonsin to leave office early.
   Menem has said the higher rates are ``anti-popular.''
   Measures reportedly being developed by the economy
minister-designate, Miguel Roig, include an across-the-board wage
raise, easy access to Central Bank credit, and a new currency to
replace the austral.
   It was unclear how the military issue, which has brought on three
insurrections against Alfonsin, would be resolved.
   Alfonsin took office in December 1983 for a six-year term after
elections that ended rule by military dictators since 1976. He was
barred by the consitution from seeking re-election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890611-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-89 1509EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Iran     06-11 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran,0649</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Million Flock to Khomeini Memorial Service</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Iranians died and thousands fainted as
huge crowds flocked to the grave of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini on
Sunday for a memorial service marking a week since his death.
   Iran's most powerful leaders were among the more than 1 million
mourners at Beheshte Zahra cemetery, 10 miles south of Tehran,
according to Iranian press reports monitored in Nicosia.
   ``Soon this site will become a shrine to attract the Moslems of
the world,'' said Parliament speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani, who broke
into tears during his speech. ``This is a center which radiates
heavenly light.''
   In Islam, the seventh and 40th days after death are considered a
time for special mourning rites. Free food and drink was distributed
around the grave.
   Iran's state-run television showed mourners beating their heads
and chests with clenched fists in the Shiite Moslem expression of
grief and chanting ``Khomeini, Khomeini, why did you leave us?''
   But the atmosphere appeared calmer than during Tuesday's burial,
which was delayed for six hours after some in the hysterical crowd
of 2 million tore pieces from Khomeini's white shroud and sent the
body falling to the ground.
   The 86-year-old patriarch died June 3 after suffering a heart
attack. There were eight deaths and 11,000 injuries in subsequent
three days of mourning.
   On Sunday, one man died of a heart attack and another died after
falling from a cargo container used for television cameras,
according to press reports.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency said the mourners were
so densely packed during the afternoon ceremony that on average one
person fainted every second in temperatures around 96.
   The sick were passed overhand to one of 23 mobile medical units
stationed around the site and more than 1,000 doctors and medical
workers were on duty, the news agency reported. More serious
injuries were rushed to nearby hospitals in one of 250 ambulances.
   The television, also monitored in Nicosia, showed a shrine built
from four metal cargo containers to stop crowds from carrying off
the dirt. The containers were covered in green, a holy color for
Islam, and were topped with a golden dome and a black flag.
   The television showed weeping mourners gripping a metal grille
built around the structure, trying to touch and kiss the shrine,
which they consider sacred.
   Those unable to reach it threw clothes and other articles to the
guards standing on top the containers. The guards touched them to
the shrine and threw them back.
   ``It would take a stone heart to stay composed at such a time,''
Rafsanjani said in his speech. Khomeini's 43-year-old son, Ahmad,
was reported too overcome to speak.
   A crop-dusting plane sprayed rosewater on the mourners, and
helicopters circled overhead, showering the crowds with flowers.
   The agency said crowds began collecting at the grave site on
Saturday night and swelled to almost 2 miles wide. There were
unprecedented traffic jams on the expressway leading to the cemetery.
   In a related development, Iranian opposition leaders said exiled
Iranians living in the United States and Europe have flocked to
rebel training camps, reopened after the death of Khomeini, a
guerrilla spokesman said Sunday.
   The National Liberation Army, the armed wing of the Baghdad-based
Mujahedeen Khalq, received many new supporters in the past week and
sent them to camps on the Iraq-Iran border, according to spokesman
Farid Suliamani.
   The camps were closed after the Aug. 20 U.N.-mediated cease-fire
in the eight-year Iran-Iraq war then reopened in a show of strength
following Khomeini's death, according to diplomatic sources. They
said, however, there was no indication the rebels would attack Iran
in violation of the cease-fire.
   The rebels fought alongside Iraq in the gulf war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
