<FIRST>r w AM-EasternEurope     06-11 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern Europe,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Ambassador Sees Bright Future For Hungary ... Unless</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With accelerating economic reform and political
liberalization, Hungary could emerge as a ``Western country'' within
the next decade, the U.S. ambassador to Budapest said Sunday.
   At the same time, Ambassador Mark Palmer cautioned that under
certain conditions the Soviet Union might again use military force
to reassert its control in Hungary or elsewhere in Eastern Europe.
   ``I think the Brezhnev Doctrine is not dead, that there are
circumstances under which the Soviets would intervene,'' he said.
``Hungary's a little less of a concern to them, I would say, than
the militarily more important countries of East Germany,
Czechoslovakia and Poland, but I would not rule out the possibility
of their intervening again.''
   Under the Brezhnev Doctrine, named for late Soviet President
Leonid I. Brezhnev, Moscow reserved the right to intervene _ as it
did in Hungary in 1956 and in Czechoslovakia in 1968 _ to preserve
communist regimes in Eastern Europe.
   Palmer, interviewed on the ABC program ``This Week With David
Brinkley,'' was asked about the longer-term prospects for Hungary,
which recently began taking down its ``Iron Curtain'' barbed wire
and fortifications along its border with Austria.
   The envoy said the outlook depends partly on what the United
States and other Western nations do.
   ``If we come into these countries with our political parties, our
trade unions, with our ideas, our values and our institutions, our
churches, our universities, our foundations, I think there's a real
chance that what you will see 10 years from today in Hungary is a
Western country,'' Palmer said.
   Also interviewed on the program was John Davis, U.S. ambassador
to Poland, where candidates backed by the Solidarity movement won a
resounding victory in parliamentary elections last week.
   Davis was asked whether Solidarity would now be a permanent
political force in Poland, or could be suppressed again in a way
comparable to the martial law crackdown in 1981.
   ``I think it's back to stay,'' he replied.
   Davis added: ``I think that Solidarity has proved through its
nonviolence, its responsible attitude and its willingness to share
power in the country that it is a partner that the government can
look forward to working with.
   ``In fact, the situation now is that the government in Poland,
the communist government, cannot pass any legislation without the
agreement of Solidarity,'' the ambassador said.
</TEXT>
