<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-89 1537EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-ChelseaSchools Bjt   06-11 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chelsea Schools, Bjt,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dukakis Walks Tightrope in Signing Chelsea School Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unprecedented experiment in public education is
about to begin with Gov. Michael S. Dukakis expected to sign a bill
Monday that will let Boston University take over the troubled school
system in the city of Chelsea.
   The plan, approved by the Legislature after months of sometimes
bitter discussion, will link a public school system with one of the
highest dropout rates in the state _ 17 percent _ to a world-class
university with all its financial and educational resources.
   Boston University will get the prestige of conducting an
educational experiment never before tried in the United States, one
that will be watched closely and possibly duplicated by universities
around the country.
   ``One of the things I think we'd like to encourage in this state
is innovation and experimentation,'' Dukakis said at a news
conference. ``And there's no question this is innovative and
experimental.''
   ``We have a bill which I think has real promise for the future of
the schoolchildren in Chelsea,'' Dukakis said. ``It's an experiment,
and like most experiments, it is one that has to be tried before we
know whether it will succeed.''
   Under the plan, BU will run the 3,600-student system for 10 years
and pump in money from private donors and foundations for a variety
of new programs, including early childhood education, counseling and
nutritional services.
   Chelsea schools have been woefully underfunded, according to
officials in the largely Hispanic, working-class city of 25,000
outside Boston. Chelsea has seen its tax base shrink and faces cuts
of about $2.8 million in next year's school budget because of a
state budget crunch.
   BU's refusal to agree to any language guaranteeing open meetings
while orally promising to abide by state open-meeting laws had held
up the bill and had put Dukakis in a difficult position once the
measure reached his desk.
   Local teachers unions and the American Federation of Teachers,
which endorsed Dukakis in his bid for president last year, had
complained that the pact would allow BU to make decisions behind
closed doors. But a veto would have set up Dukakis for an
embarrassment, since the Legislature had passed the bill with enough
votes to override.
   On Friday, however, the governor said he would sign the bill _
and also direct the state Board of Education to set up a monitoring
panel to make sure BU abides by the open-meeting and public-records
laws.
   That move seemed to satisfy several factions that were
practically at one another's throats days earlier.
   BU administrators were delighted with the announcement, saying it
allowed them to begin raising the roughly $30 million they hope to
spend over the next decade.
   Hispanics opposed the agreement, saying university officials have
ignored requests for more information about bilingual programs.
   BU President John Silber said he would heed concerns raised.
   ``We are not going to privatize the schools,'' Silber said. ``We
are going to manage the public schools and they are going to remain
public.''
   For higher education there could be a long-term benefit if the BU
experiment succeeds.
   ``Universities are looking at themselves and saying, `What is our
role in terms of the reform movement in education?''' said Peter
Greer, dean of the BU education school. ``One thing universities
have said is say how bad the entering freshmen are.''
</TEXT>
