<HEAD>Burmese Troops Attack Ethnic Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAE SOT, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,500 Burmese troops attacked a
stronghold of ethnic Karen rebels near the Thai on border Sunday,
Thai border police reported.
   They said about 700 Karen guerrillas were defending the Pa Loo
base and about 2,000 civilians had fled the area.
   Burmese forces began pounding the camp with hundreds of shells
and bombs early Sunday, said the police, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   There were no immediate casualty reports from Sunday's fighting,
which was still heavy late in the day.
   However, Karen sources said 22 Burmese soldiers and six rebels
had been killed since battles began around the camp on June 1. They
said 31 government troops were wounded along with 13 Karens.
   Karens are the largest of a dozen ethnic rebel groups which have
battled for 40 years seeking more autonomy from the central
government. Authorities opened an intensive campaign last October to
crush the Karen insurgency.
