<FIRST>r i AM-Iraq-CrashProbe     06-11 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iraq-Crash Probe,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Issued on Copter Crash That Killed Defense Minister</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HASAN MROUE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A committee investigating a helicopter
crash that killed Iraq's defense minister determined the crew lost
control of the chopper during a sandstorm, the official Iraqi News
Agency reported Sunday.
   The agency, monitored in Nicosia, said the committee's report
blamed ``extraordinarily bad weather conditions and lack of
visibility coupled with a sandstorm'' for the crash that killed Gen.
Adnan Khairallah.
   There were no indications of mechanical trouble, an explosion or
fire aboard the U.S.-made Bell military helicopter, which had flown
for only 603 hours when it crashed in northern Iraq on May 5.
   Bell helicopters normally are used by Iraq's President Saddam
Hussein and his aides when traveling inside the country.
   Khairallah, who was deputy armed forces commander-in-chief and a
close confidante of Saddam, was killed along with six others, on a
flight to Baghdad from a mountain resort near Mosul, 280 miles
northwest of the capital.
   He was considered the second-most powerful man in Iraq after
Saddam.
   The helicopter went down near the village of Kweir, close to the
main Mosul-Kerkuk road, an uncultivated area inhabited by Bedouin
tribes, the report said.
   Khairallah, who was Saddam's brother-in-law but had recently been
at odds with the president, was the third senior Iraqi official to
die in a helicopter crash in the past 18 months. Diplomats in
Baghdad said Saddam and Khairallah had a brief misunderstanding in
late 1988 over the president's treatment of his oldest son, Odai.
   The report said the meteorological department at the Firnass air
base had warned of possible sandstorms and bad visibility in
northern Iraq.
   The Iraqi News Agency said the investigating committee included
representatives of the army transportation staff, the air force and
air defense command, military intelligence and general security
service, the Iraqi intelligence agency and the military's technical
department.
</TEXT>
