<DOCNO> AP890611-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-89 1608EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China-WorldReax     06-11 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-World Reax,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Korea Tells Washington to Butt Out, But World Still Angry</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHIL BROWN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea declared solidarity Sunday with Chinese
hard-liners and rebuked U.S. complaints about their crackdown, but
Hong Kong demonstrators burned a coffin of the ``Chinese soul''
during more worldwide protests.
   In San Francisco, two men identified as Chinese diplomats
declared they could no longer lie about their government's
suppression of pro-democracy protesters and asked for asylum in the
United States.
   The Bush administration, many leaders around the world, and
thousands of protesters have been speaking out against the Chinese
government since it ordered soldiers to move against the protesters
on June 3-4. The death toll remains uncertain, but U.S. intelligence
estimates say 3,000 died.
   The United States decided to suspend arms sales to China.
   In a commentary carried by the official North Korean News Agency,
that country said: ``No matter what may happen in China, it is not a
business of the United States across the ocean.''
   The dispatch, monitored in Tokyo, added that Washington ``cannot
bar the triumphant advance of socialism.''
   Chinese troops fought with North Korea against U.S.-led U.N.
forces that came to South Korea's aid in the 1950-53 Korean War.
   In Hong Kong, protesters burned a cardboard coffin marked
``Chinese soul'' next to the local office of China's official Xinhua
News Agency. In keeping with Chinese funeral customs, the coffin as
well as wreaths and banners were set on fire a week after the deaths.
   During a separate rally in a downtown park, thousands of people
watched actors portray Beijing residents braving bullets fired by
troops.
   Organizers urged the Chinese government not to arrest
demonstrators, called for strikes in Hong Kong and China, and
appealed to Chinese-funded companies to break with Chinese
authorities.
   U.S. educators evacuated from China to Hong Kong said Sunday they
fear the departure of foreigners from China will leave student
protesters and others there more vulnerable.
   ``We're worried not only about the safety of the students. We're
worried about the safety of everybody in the university that we
knew,'' said Larry Slifman, an economist from Washington, D.C. He
had been teaching at Wuhan University.
   At a protest of about 5,000 people in San Francisco, two men
identified as diplomats at the Chinese consulate said they no longer
could support their government and were defecting.
   ``We are supposed to tell you that no one was injured or killed.
Why? Because we are diplomats. But we won't fake it here,'' one of
them said.
   The FBI confirmed the asylum request but did not release the
men's names. Lee Man-kar, an editor at San Francisco's Chinese
Times, identified the two as Zhou Li-ming, vice consul for cultural
affairs; and Zhang Li-man, acting consul for overseas affairs.
   At least 5,000 Chinese students and British supporters in London,
many chanting ``Long live freedom!'' marched from Chinatown to the
Chinese Embassy, following behind a banner proclaiming: ``Condemn
the murderous government in China.''
   In Sydney, Australian Prime Minister Bob Hawke said concern for
fundamental human rights ``transcends national boundaries'' and that
China's leaders have lost international standing.
   The newspaper Tokyo Shimbun reported Japan is reluctant to
provide more development assistance to China unless its government
takes responsibility for the violence. However, the report did not
say exactly what China would have to do.
   Malaysia's Home Ministry said it would keep tabs on domestic
supporters of the Chinese protest movement for fear they might
threaten Malaysian security.
   Malaysia has long been wary of China, which gives moral support
to communist guerrillas on the Malaysia-Thailand border.
</TEXT>
