<DOCNO> AP890611-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-89 1706EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Year-RoundSchool     06-11 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Year-Round School,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Orleans Board to Vote on Year-Round School Experiment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Summer may be over almost before it's begun
for students at two elementary schools where officials are planning
to try the Three Rs year-round.
   The Orleans Parish School Board meets Monday to make its final
decison, after giving tentative approval in February to add 40 days
to the school year at the two city schools.
   For pupils at Robert Moton and Johnson C. Lockett elementary
schools who volunteer to take part, it would mean returning to
school July 10 instead of Sept. 5 like the rest of the city's
students. The schools have a combined enrollment of 1,400.
   Its estimated cost would be $703,000 and some supporters fear
board members might balk at the expense of the plan when they meet
on Monday.
   ``We really have to try a model to work out the kinks,'' board
member Woody Koppel said Sunday.
   He said he expects a unanimous vote, even though some board
members may have reservations about parts of the plan.
   ``It's expensive but it's worth spending the money to try it
out.''
   Plans call for the money to come from the federal government's
Chapter I supplemental program for disadvantaged students _ about
three-quarters of the students at each school are from low-income
families, Koppel said.
   But federal rather than local tax dollars won't mean the program
will be judged any less strictly, he said.
   ``It has to prove that it's cost-effective and can improve test
scores and deportment in the schools,'' said Koppel. ``We will see
after the first year how well this program is judged.''
   He said the program is planned for both Moton, which had 798
students last year, and Lockett, which had 710, because they serve
students from the same general area _ an area which includes two
housing projects.
   ``Sometimes the kids move around. We don't want a situation where
they move from one school to another and lose the services,'' he
said.
   Nelka Smith is one parent who will be disappointed if the
year-round plan is postponed.
   ``Year-round school is a plus,'' said Smith, who was at Moton on
Thursday to pick up report cards for her five children, all of whom
made the honor roll and earned perfect attendance certificates.
   ``A longer school year would give the children something better
to do than playing in the street, especially in that dirty water
after it rains,'' she said.
   Like other Moton parents, Smith said the year-round program will
give the children an alternative to the drugs and violence prevalent
in the nearby Desire housing project area.
   ``I'd rather see them here safe than exposed to drugs in the
streets,'' said Sandra Doyle, whose three children attend Moton.
``Three months without nothing to do is too much time wasted.''
   While most American children spend 180 days in the classroom,
school terms in Japan last 240 days. The New Orleans experiment
would be for a 220-day term. Two American high schools offer an
extended year.
   California has year-round schools, Koppel said, but that program
was started because there were too few school buildings rather than
as an attempt to boost learning.
   Moton and Lockett teachers were given the option of transferring
to other schools, and student participation is voluntary.
   Lockett Principal Herbert Dunn said all but two of his teachers
signed up for the year-round program.
   ``The parents are enthused about it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
