<DOCNO> AP890611-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-89 1653EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-AM-Lebanon-Hostages     06-11 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AM-Lebanon-Hostages,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wife Appeals for Release of Missing Briton</HEAD>
<HEAD>By RODEINA KENAAN</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of a missing Briton who was
believed kidnapped a month ago marked his 75th birthday Sunday with
a tearful televised appeal to the Syrian army to ``find Jacky for
me.''
   ``Our 48th wedding anniversary is on June the 18th. Please send
him home for me,'' sobbed Sunny Mann in a 90-second plea over the
Christian-controlled Lebanese Broadcasting Corp. network.
   Jack Mann, a World War II pilot, disappeared in Moslem west
Beirut May 12. The couple has lived in west Beirut for more than 40
years.
   ``I'm not a young woman to stand the continuous pain of not
knowing if he's dead or alive,'' Mrs. Mann said, reading from a
prepared statement.
   She then removed her glasses, faced the camera and as her eyes
welled with tears, said, ``We love you darling; happy birthday.''
   A terrorist group, the Cells of Armed Struggle, claimed in a
statement delivered to a Western news agency on the day Mann
disappeared that it had kidnapped a Briton. It did not give any name.
   The group demanded the release of comrades who it said were
jailed in London in connection with the 1987 killing of Palestinian
cartoonist Ali Naji Al-Adhami.
   It did not identify the people allegedly jailed and Scotland Yard
said no arrests have been made in the case.
   Mrs. Mann said in her plea, ``I am appealing to the Syrians who
are in charge of security in west Beirut. Find Jacky for me. You
have found other hostages, Lebanese and foreigners. I know you made
several inquiries but please try harder.''
   The Syrians maintain an estimated 12,000 troops in west Beirut
and parts of Lebanon under an Arab League mandate.
   Fifteen Westerners, not counting Mann, are missing in Lebanon and
it is believed they were kidnapped by Moslem extremists. Nine
Americans are among the hostages. Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press, has been held the longest.
He was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890611-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-89 1704EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Iran-Opposition 1stLd-Writethru a0634 06-11 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Opposition, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0634,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iranian Rebels Flooded With Recruits After Khomeini Death, Sources
Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads grafs 1-2, moving up Khomeini death. Pick up 3d graf:
The National Liberation...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian opposition forces, hoping to take
advantage of the disarray in Iran following the death of Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini, have reopened camps in Iraq to train thousands of
recruits, according to diplomats.
   They said Iranians living in exile in Europe and the United
States have flocked to Iraq to join the National Liberation Army of
Iran since Khomeini's death June 3.
   The National Liberation Army is the military wing of the
Mujahedeen Khalq, or People's Holy Warriors, the main Iranian
opposition group.
   Thousands of exiled sympathizers were immediately sent to rebel
bases along the Iran-Iraq border for training, according to a
mujahedeen spokesman.
   ``A stream of our supporters has been pouring in and they are
being given proper training in our bases here,'' said Farid
Suliamani, a spokesman for the Baghdad-based organization. He did
not give figures on new recruits.
   Witnesses said dozens of military vehicles carrying rebel
fighters were seen Thursday and Friday near northern Suliamaniya
heading toward rebel camps on the border with Iran. The vehicles had
Farsi markings and bore mujahedeen emblems, they said.
   Border camps were closed after a United Nations cease-fire halted
the eight-year Iran-Iraq war on Aug. 20. The Mujahedeen fought
alongside Iraq in the war and also halted operations inside Iran
following the truce.
   But rebel leaders put their forces _ estimated at 20,000 _ on
alert after Khomeini underwent surgery May 23 to stop intestinal
bleeding.
   After the patriarch's death, opposition leader Massoud Rajavi
called on Iranians to prepare to welcome the rebels and help them
when they move into Iran ``at the appropriate moment.'' Rebel camps
were reopened in a show of force, diplomats said.
   The diplomatic sources spoke on the condition they not be
identified.
   But there has been no indication that the rebels are planning
military action.
   Military analysts do not believe the rebels are strong enough to
topple the Iranian government alone unless a power struggle
develops. And despite earlier indications of factional fighting,
Iran's new leader, President Ali Khamenei seems to be consolidating
his position, sources said.
   In addition, any military move would need approval from the Iraqi
government. It is thought unlikely that Baghdad would permit any
action that might jeopardize the temporary truce with Iran or impede
progress in deadlocked peace talks.
   One diplomat said although it was unlikely the rebels would move
across the border while the cease-fire holds they might take
advantage of any serious truce violation to attack Iranian positions
or set up rebel bases inside Iran. Mujahedeen officials said the
group's military strength has increased steadily since the
cease-fire and that months of intensive training in Iraq have made
it ``a far more effective military force than before.''
   The rebels were allied with Khomeini in the struggle to topple
the late Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi. But in 1980-81, a year after
Khomeini took power, he turned on the group and other leftist
factions, killing and imprisoning tens of thousands of people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890611-0051 </DOCNO>
