<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-89 1724EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-China 1stLd-Writethru a0608 06-11 0793</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-China, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0608,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ambassador Says Would Be ``Terrible Mistake'' For U.S. To Break Relations</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS 4 grafs after pvs 8th graf bgng ``Lilley responded:
...'' to UPDATE with Bush, State Department reaction to arrest warrant
for dissident holed up at U.S. embassy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. ambassador to China, James R. Lilley,
said Sunday it would be a ``terrible mistake'' for the United States
to give up on maintaining relations with China despite the Beijing
government's harsh crackdown on the democratic reform movement.
   Lilley said U.S. policy toward China needs to respond to the
immediate situation there but also take a long-term approach rather
than seek any kind of ``quick fix.''
   The envoy's comments came in a telephone interview from Beijing
broadcast on the CBS program ``Face the Nation.''
   ``I think we've gone through many ups and downs with China, and I
think right now we're going through a down,'' Lilley said. ``But I
don't think we should sort of give up on it. I think that would be a
terrible mistake.''
   He said the United States can continue to have some influence in
China through avenues including Voice of America broadcasts,
training of Chinese students and ``in the multitude of business
decisions that are made every day on the basis of investment climate
and trading atmosphere.''
   ``What we do is we play for the long term, and we don't look for
a quick fix. ... We look for a long term solution. And I think
that's what we're working towards,'' Lilley said.
   The ambassador was asked about leading Chinese dissident Fang
Lizhi, who has taken refuge in the U.S. embassy in Beijing and is
seeking political asylum.
   Lilley responded: ``I would prefer not to discuss that situation.
I will say that I have had conversations with them (Chinese
officials) in the last two or three days. ... It's a very sensitive
thing, and it's best to do it and shut up.''
   Lilley gave no indication during the interview that he was aware
the Chinese government had issued an arrest warrant for Lizhi and
his wife, Li Shuxian, on charges of ``committing crimes of
counterrevolutionary propaganda and instigation.''
   Asked if the Chinese had approached U.S. officials about the two
dissidents, Kenneth Bailes, a State Department spokesman refused to
comment on the report and on any aspect of the situation.
   Upon arrival at the White house from the Camp David weekend
retreat, esident Bush declined to give a reaction to the Chinese
demand.
   As reporters shouted questions he cupped his hand to his ear and
said: ``I can't hear a thing. This is not an appropriate time.''
   The head of an organization supporting U.S.-China trade and
business ventures said American companies should first take steps to
ensure the safety of their personnel in China, then carefully
reassess their business prospects.
   Roger Sullivan, president of the U.S.-China Business Council,
said that in the short term, ``Nobody's talking about business as
usual. Business with China has been devastated, and it's very
important for us to bring home to the Chinese people that their
government did it.''
   He estimated that up until the current turmoil, the American
business presence in China totalled 8,000 to 9,000 people, with
about 300 U.S. companies having investment contracts worth $3.4
billion.
   ``Companies are taking their people out. That's the first thing
to do. I mean you've got to protect the safety and security of your
people, and then take a long look at and test your assumptions about
how you're going to be able to continue _ if indeed you're going to
be able to continue at all,'' Sullivan said.
   Also appearing on the CBS program was Sen. Alfonse D'Amato,
R-N.Y., who said he expects to see congressional action within the
next 10 days on economic sanctions against China, including a cutoff
of high technology.
   D'Amato said the United States should act as a ``catalyst'' in
promoting multilateral sanctions against China by Western European
countries and Japan.
   Rep. Stephen J. Solarz, D-N.Y., chairman of the House Foreign
Affairs subcommittee on Asian and Pacific affairs, also endorsed a
strategy of seeking multilateral economic sanctions.
   Interviewed on CNN's ``Newsmaker Sunday,'' Solarz said the United
States should deprive China of ``any special concessions or credits
which they've been receiving in the past which we ordinarily
wouldn't give to a communist regime which engages in the fundamental
abuse of the human rights of its own people.''
   Solarz was asked about the question of maintaining electronic
listening posts in China which help monitor Soviet missile tests.
   He responded that ``in terms of the listening posts, I believe
that those are mutually beneficial and so I don't think we need to
be overly concerned about them.''
</TEXT>
