<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-11 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Storms Loom Over The South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy thunderstorms and at least one tornado developed Sunday
over the South, and wet weather was scattered elsewhere across the
central part of the nation.
   An upper air disturbance moving across the southern Plains
triggered strong thunderstorms in humid, unstable air from the
central Gulf Coast and the lower Mississippi Valley into southern
Missouri.
   A tornado was produced by a severe thunderstorm near Bee Branch,
Ark., whileheavy rain that started falling Saturday caused rivers
and streams to rise across the southern Plains.
   Up to 7 inches of rain fell in parts of southeastern Kansas late
Saturday and early Sunday, forcing some rivers and streams out of
their banks. By 6 a.m. Sunday, Coffeyville had 7.2 inches of rain,
including 4 inches in one 45-minute period, and minor street
flooding was reported there and in nearby Caney.
   In north-central Kansas, vehicles were stranded throughout Beloit
after 3 inches fell in one hour late Saturday. At the Elks Club in
the center of town, the hoods of some cars were covered by water for
a short time.
   Two to 4 inches of rain fell overnight around Abilene, Texas,
which caused more than a foot of water to run over the spillway of
Lytle Lake.
   Flooding was expected in rural areas along the Verdigris River in
northern Oklahoma. Showers and some thunderstorms were scattered
across eastern Kansas and northeastern Oklahoma, with more
thunderstorms expected during the night across northern Texas.
   A cold front pushing across the northern Plains and central
Rockies produced showers and thunderstorms from the Great Basin of
Nevada and western Utah to the Dakotas.
   Elsewhere, thunderstorms were scattered across the Florida
Peninsula.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 51
degrees at Presque Isle and Caribou, Maine, to 98 at Needles,
Calif., and Laredo, Texas. Sunday's low in the 48 contiguous states
was 31 at Alamosa, Colo.
   For Monday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast from Florida
and much of the Gulf Coast region across the Mississippi and Ohio
valleys, and the Great Lakes to eastern sections of the central and
southern Plains. Showers were expected across the northern Plains
and the northern Rockies. Showers and thunderstorms developing later
in the day were forecast across the central Rockies.
   Highs in the 50s and 60s were predicted from central Montana
across the northern Plains and upper Mississippi Valley to the upper
Great Lakes; in the 90s from Florida and southern Georgia across the
Gulf Coast region, much of Texas, the southern Rockies and interior
valleys of California and Oregon; above 100 over the desert
Southwest, interior valleys of southern California, and along the
Rio Grande Valley in Texas; and in the 70s and 80s across the
remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
