<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Nagy     06-11 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Nagy,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gov't TV Shows Film of Trial Of Executed Reformist Premier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungarian television on Sunday showed
brief film footage of the trial of Premier Imre Nagy, a leader of
the 1956 anti-Soviet revolt who was executed in 1958.
   Nagy and the bodies of several of his close associates were
buried in unmarked graves, but the remains are to be reburied during
a ceremony Friday.
   Reformers, including Communist Party members, have claimed Nagy
and the others were convicted at an unconstitutional ``show trial''
and said they should be ``rehabilitated.''
   The film clip showed Nagy and some of his supporters being led
into a courtroom where they were charged with crimes against the
state.
   It was shown during a half-hour news program on the 1956 revolt
when Nagy's government sought to organize multiparty free elections
and sever Hungary's ties with the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact alliance.
   Soviet tanks crushed the revolt and Nagy and hundreds of other
government and political leaders were arrested.
   The bodies of Nagy and a few associates were dumped in a grave in
a cemetery in suburban Budpest. During Friday's ceremony, which will
be televised, the remains will be buried again in the same cemetery.
   Re-evaluation of the revolt began after hard-line Communist Party
chief Janos Kadar, who succeeded Nagy, was ousted in May 1988 under
strong criticism from reformers.
   In a statement last week the Communist Party leadership called
Nagy a ``significant'' figure in post-World War II Hungary.
   Leading Communist reformer Imre Pozsgay, in an interview on
Sunday's television program, said the time has come ``to face the
facts of what happened between Oct. 1956 and June 1958.''
   He said Nagy's trial was a ``political trial on trumped up
charges.''
   Foreign Minister Gyula Horn, who also was interviewed on the
program, said ``many of the tasks he (Nagy) set remain important to
this day.''
</TEXT>
