<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-89 1840EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-Wright-HouseSeat     06-11 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wright-House Seat,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Republicans Aren't Pinning Hopes on Wright Seat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Party officials are playing
down their chances for Rep. Jim Wright's 12th District seat despite
an ethics investigation that forced the House Speaker to resign.
   ``It's like running the 100-yard dash between a Republican and a
Democrat, and giving the Democrat an 80-yard head start,'' said
Brian Epstein, a Republican political consultant in Fort Worth.
``It's not a fair race.''
   Republican officials point to several factors in their decision
to focus their efforts elsewhere.
   The district, which includes all of Fort Worth and most of its
surrounding communities, was drawn by Wright himself. It is full of
blue-collar Democrats and boasts a solid bloc of minority voters
that averages 30 percent to 40 percent of the voter turnout.
   In addition, Wright brought home more defense contracts, jobs and
federal funding than any other large urban area in the country
received, according to a computer study earlier this year by The
Dallas Morning News.
   Many residents view Wright as a martyr in an unjust political
war. And two of the strongest of possible GOP candidates, Fort Worth
Mayor Bob Bolen and Tarrant County Judge Roy English, have indicated
they are not interested in the seat.
   Finally, state Sen. Hugh Parmer, a formidable Democrat and
longtime friend of Wright, is considered a viable candidate.
   Ed Rollins, deputy chairman of the National Republican
Congressional Committee, said the district ``was drawn for the
Democratic leadership.'' Steve Hollern, chairman of the Tarrant
County Republican Party, called the seat ``marginally winnable.''
   The 12th District seat is one of three formerly Democratic seats
to be filled in upcoming special elections. Claude Pepper of Florida
died May 30 at the age of 88, and Majority Whip Tony Coelho of
California announced last month he would resign rather than face an
ethics investigation similar to Wright's.
   Rollins indicated last week that Republicans probably would
target Pepper's seat more heavily than the Fort Worth district.
   ``You cannot attack Jim Wright,'' Epstein told The Morning News.
``Anywhere in Texas, his name is mud, except in the Congressional
District 12.''
   Gov. Bill Clements can set a date for a special election not less
than 36 days after Wright submits his resignation from the House.
Wright indicated that would happen by the end of June.
   Republican officials say as many as 15 potential candidates have
begun to scope out potential supporters and financial backers, but
the field is not expected to narrow for at least another week.
   The potential GOP candidates include Alvarado businessman Don
McNiel, who unsuccessfully challenged Wright in 1986; state Rep.
Bill Carter; Erma Johnson, former chairwoman of the Dallas-Fort
Worth International Airport board; and former Fort Worth City
Council member Russell Lancaster.
</TEXT>
