<HEAD>Ex-President Reagan Makes First Trip Abroad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Ronald Reagan arrived Sunday night
for a private visit _ his first trip abroad since leaving the White
House in January.
   Reagan, accompanied by his wife Nancy, arrived at London's
Heathrow Airport aboard a private Boeing 727 jetliner. They were
greeted by U.S. Ambassador Henry Catto and former Foreign Secretary
Francis Pym.
   The Reagans waved to onlookers before entering a limousine and
driving off without comment.
   They were scheduled to stay in Battersea Lodge, a private home
owned by magazine publisher and author Malcolm Forbes.
   Reagan is to deliver the Churchill Memorial Lecture on Tuesday.
The English Speaking Union invited Reagan to present an address on
``The problems, perils, challenges and opportunities confronting the
English-speaking peoples of today.''
   Last month Prince Philip presented the Churchill Award to Reagan
in Los Angeles. Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, Reagan's host for
dinner on Tuesday, is among four recipients of the award.
   On Wednesday the Reagans have been invited to lunch with Queen
Elizabeth II at Buckingham Palace, and he will be honored that
evening at a dinner sponsored by the Ronald Reagan Library
Foundation.
   Reagan last visited London on his way back from the Moscow summit
in June 1988. He also visited Britain in 1982 and 1984.
