<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--MethanolFire     06-11 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Methanol Fire,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>Methanol Fire To Be Allowed to Burn Out</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PLAQUEMINE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 2.5 million-gallon tank of methanol set
afire by lightning continued to burn Sunday as officials allowed it
to burn itself out.
   ``According to what they say, it should be burned out before
daylight,'' said Iberville Parish Sheriff's Deputy Roy Hebert.
   ``The tank is folding in as the fire burns itself down,'' Hugh
Lansford, manager at the six-month-old Ashland Chemical Co. plant
where the tank was located, said late Saturday. He said there was
little danger the fire would spread to nearby tanks.
   Just to be sure, state police said, firefighters sprayed water on
the burning tank and another tank of methanol, or methyl alcohol,
about 400 feet away to keep them as cool as possible.
   Damage appeared to be confined to the tank and no injuries were
reported.
   The plant turns natural gas into methanol, a high-quality fuel
used for, among other things, drag racers. The fire was reported
Saturday afternoon.
