<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-89 2032EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-Wright'sResignation     06-11 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wright's Resignation,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethics Committee Offered Wright Deal to Resign, Newspaper Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the House ethics committee,
not Speaker Jim Wright, initiated an attempt to strike a deal and
negotiate his resignation, the Dallas Times Herald reported Sunday.
   ``Everybody made it sound like Jim Wright went in on his knees
and asked for a deal,'' one senior Democratic source told the
newspaper. ``That is the complete opposite of what is true.''
   The Times Herald reported that numerous sources who asked not to
be named said the house speaker's resignation began with a call from
ethics committee Chairman Julian Dixon, D-Calif, to Rep. Louis
Stokes, D-Ohio, the former ethics chairman.
   Dixon said Wright's resignation would ``spare the House a harsh
and divisive confrontation,'' sources told the newspaper. Dixon said
the committee could drop some of the 69 allegations against Wright
by accepting portions of his legal motions filed the previous week,
if the speaker would agree to resign.
   Stokes relayed the message to Rep. Robert Torricelli, a New
Jersey Democrat who joined Wright's defense team several weeks
earlier. He passed the information on to the speaker.
   Wright, who told Torricelli to go ahead with negotiations,
reportedly said he was interested in an agreement if it would clear
the names of his wife, Betty, and friend George Mallick. Mallick had
been accused of providing Betty Wright with a phony job and improper
gifts.
   As negotiations continued, Wright turned down offers that would
have included continuing the censure over the sale of his book,
``Reflections of a Public Man,'' and the stipulation that Wright
step down within 24 hours.
   Wright reportedly said there would be no ``quid pro quo''
agreement for his resignation in exchange for exoneration on charges.
   Wright's representatives met with the committee's outside
counsel, Richard Phelan. Phelan said he had votes of all six
Republicans and at least one Democrat, Rep. Chester Atkins, D-Mass.,
to continue the investigation into other allegations against Wright
for several months.
   When those talks failed, Thomas Foley, D-Wash., then the House
majority leader and now the Speaker, was called in as a mediator.
The relationship between Dixon and Wright had deteriorated to the
point that neither man trusted the other, the newspaper reported.
   Then the ethics committee convened, with some Republicans
reportedly angered by the negotiations. But three hours later, the
group had heard nothing from Wright.
   ``If he wanted to make an offer, we were sitting there,'' said
Rep. John Myers, R-Indiana, who added that he was opposed to any
deals.
   To Wright's closest allies, the former speaker was the victim of
a ``setup.''
   But John Buckley of the National Republican Congressional
Committee disputed the claim.
   ``It is quite a typical Democratic ploy once they have lost to
claim that they were tricked or the tactics against them were
illegitimate,'' Buckley said. ``Wright's decline was inevitable,
whether it happened as quickly as it did or not. He was going down.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890611-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-89 2039EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     06-11 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jordanian Foreign Minister Says Iranian Troops in Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Marwan Kassem says two
regiments of Iranian soldiers have arrived in war-ravaged Lebanon,
the Jordan Times newspaper reported Sunday.
   ``The Iranian military presence in the country is an attempt
designed to partition the sovereign Arab state ... through deepening
sectarianism, which in turn facilitates Israeli plans,'' he was
quoted as saying.
   The English-language daily quoted him as saying two Iranian
regiments had arrived in Lebanon and that more could arrive soon.
But there was no indication when the troops had arrived or how many
men were in each regiment.
   Sources in the eastern Baalbek region of Lebanon, a
fundamentalist stronghold, said 500 Revolutionary Guards had arrived
last month to reinforce the 3,000-strong garrison in the area.
   The contingent has been based there since early 1983, months
after the Israel invasion of Lebanon. Their stated purpose was to
fight with the Syrian army against Israel, but the Syrian troops did
not engage Israeli forces.
   Former President Amin Gemayel asked for their withdrawal several
times, severing relations with Iran over the issue in 1984.
Relations were restored in 1987.
   The contingent has been preaching Khomeini's brand of
fundamentalism among the Shiites in the Bekaa valley. It has its own
radio and television stations.
   Syria has allowed increasing Iranian influence in Lebanon,
annoying the many Arab states allied with Iraq during the 8-year
Iran-Iraq war that ended in a cease-fire last August. Those states
oppose the spread Iran's Shiite Moslem religious fundamentalism.
   Kassem was a member of a six-man Arab League committee which
tried to solve the 14-year-old Lebanese conflict earlier this year.
Rival Christian and Moslem Cabinets have been vying for power since
September, and artillery duels between their sectors in Beirut has
left more than 360 dead in the latest round of fighting that began
March 8.
   An Arab summit late last month replaced the earlier panel with a
three-man committee of Saudi Arabia's King Fahd, Morocco's King
Hassan and Algerian President Chedli Benjedid.
   The summit failed to win Syrian agreement to withdraw its 40,000
troops in Lebanon, who are backing the Moslem forces.
   The newspaper quoted Kassem as saying foreign occupation of
Lebanon could end when the Arabs can solve Lebanon's political
problem and can assure Syria it will not face Israeli threats
through Lebanon.
   Israel occupies a strip of territory in south Lebanon. Kassem
suggested Arabs could try to push for Israel's withdrawal under U.N.
Security Council resolutions _ a solution that he said might require
increased numbers of U.N. peacekeeping troops in Lebanon.
</TEXT>
