<HEAD>Weeklong Curfew Lifted in Gaza, Two Palestinians Die of Wounds</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 17 grafs to UPDATE with 2nd death Sunday and Palestinian
group pamphlet with threat. CORRECTS that Ghali met with Palestinian activist
Husseini, who is not a PLO activist. Pick up 17th graf pvs: The PLO has
rejected...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE OLSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's military command on Sunday lifted a
weeklong curfew that confined 700,000 Palestinians to their homes in
the Gaza Strip, ending one of the longest restrictions imposed in
the 18-month Arab uprising.
   A curfew remained in effect on the 53,000 Palestinians in Gaza's
Jabaliya refugee camp because of clashes there Saturday with Israeli
troops.
   Two Palestinian teen-agers injured in the refugee camp violence
died Sunday of gunshot wounds to the head, an army spokesman
reported.
   He identified the victims as Mohammed Saeed Al Shaweesh, 15, and
Musa Omar Khalil Shama, 17, and said they died at Israel's Tel
Hashomer Hospital near Tel Aviv.
   The deaths raised to at least 516 the number of Palestinians
killed since the Palestininan uprising against Israeli rule in the
West Bank and Gaza Strip began in December 1987. Twenty-two Israelis
have been killed in the violence.
   In other developments Sunday:
   _A pamphlet issued by the clandestine Unified National Leadership
of the Uprising called on Palestinians to kill one soldier or Jewish
settler for each Arab slain. ``It is our right to defend ourselves
and slaughter our enemy with knives because our blood is not cheaper
than theirs,'' it said.
   _An Egyptian Cabinet minister discussed the uprising with Israeli
politicians and a Palestinian activist who supports the Palestine
Liberation Organization.
   _Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir agreed to convene the governing
body of his right-wing Likud bloc, where he will face a challenge to
his peace plan by three of the party's leading members;
   _Israeli peace activists protested a plan to require Arab day
laborers to wait in a specially designated ``transit station'' in a
town near Tel Aviv; and
   _Another group of eight Israeli peace activists who attended a
meeting with PLO representatives in June 1987 were charged by an
Israeli court with violating the nation's anti-terror law.
   After the curfew was lifted, 4,000 cars streamed out of Gaza
carrying Arabs to their jobs in Israel for the first time in a week,
Israel radio said.
   The curfew was imposed June 4 at the start of a government
campaign to give Gazans computerized identification cards to monitor
their travel into Israel.
   No violence was reported in Gaza or the West Bank Sunday.
   Butros Ghali, the Egyptian minister of state for foreign affairs,
began a two-day visit Sunday by meeting Labor Party members. They
hope Ghali's visit, the first by an Egyptian Cabinet minister in
nearly two years, will lead Egypt to support the Israeli peace plan
for the occupied lands.
   After meeting with Finance Minister Shimon Peres, leader of the
left-wing Labor Party, Ghali told reporters: ``I believe that on
some of the things where we agree, that we must continue to work
together where we can find a peaceful solution to the Palestinian
problem.''
   Ghali also met with Faisal Husseini, a Palestinian who heads a
study center in east Jeruslalem and is a PLO supporter. After the
meeting Husseini told reporters, ``The Egyptian position, I believe,
supports the Palestinian position.'' He declined further comment.
   The PLO has rejected the peace plan, which which calls for
elections and limited automony in the West Bank and Gaza.
   In the Tel Aviv suburb of Petah Tikva, 150 peace activists
demonstrated against the town's plan to require Arab day laborers to
wait in a specially designated ``transit station.'' The Town Council
put up plastic-roofed shelters on the edge of Petah Tikva to prevent
Arab workers from loitering on the streets as they await hiring on
work crews.
   The station was to be used starting Sunday, but a town spokeman
said implementation of the plan was delayed while Town Council
members debated it. Police have objected to the plan, challenging
its legality.
   Opponents described the holding area as racist and reminiscent of
South African apartheid. ``We didn't believe they would use it,''
said Shirley Eran, a member of the 21st Year group that organized
the demonstration. ``It is shocking to think they would.''
   Shamir, the Likud leader, has threatened to resign if the July 2
meeting of the 2,600-member Central Committee rejects his peace plan.
   His party rivals, Industry and Trade Minister Ariel Sharon,
Economics Minister Yitzhak Modai and Housing and Construction
Minister David Levy, have demanded that the Central Committee amend
the plan.
   Sharon has demanded that the elections be held without
international supervision or the participation of the 140,000 Arabs
of East Jerusalem. Palestinians have insisted on both as a condition
for agreeing to elections.
   The plan is silent on both points, and would have little chance
of Palestinian acceptance if Sharon's amendments are accepted.
   The charges against the eight Israeli peace activists say they
met PLO members in Hungary and discussed political matters without
authorization. If convicted, the activists face a maximum sentence
of three years in jail.
</TEXT>
