<FIRST>u i AM-Libya-US     06-11 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Libya-US,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gadhafi Praises Bush Administration As Mature And Wise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi on Sunday praised the
Bush administration as ``wise and mature'' and said he expected
``balanced relations'' with both superpowers, the official Libyan
news agency JANA reported.
   Gadhafi's comments in Tripoli, the Libyan capital, appeared to be
part of an effort in recent months to improve relations with the
United States, which were sour under former President Ronald Reagan.
   The Libyan leader spoke to JANA, monitored in Rome, after a
ceremony marking the 19th anniversary of the eviction of U.S. forces
from bases in Libya.
   ``The Bush administration is a wise and mature administration and
understands international politics and it is not possible that it
will repeat the ignorance of Reagan and it is not possible that it
will inflict new damages to American interests and foreign policy,''
he told a JANA reporter.
   ``But contrary to that, we believe the new administration will
make up for the damage caused to America during the Reagan era and
that Great Jamahiriya (Libya) will establish balanced relations with
America and the Soviet Union,'' Gadhafi said, according to the JANA
dispatch.
   Gadhafi told The Associated Press in September that he expected
U.S. foreign policy to change from the strongly anti-Libyan stance
pursued under Reagan. The Libyan leader has also said President Bush
realized the ``irrationality'' of the Reagan policy and would make
amends for it.
   In a January interview, Gadhafi called for a dialogue with the
United States but Washington says Libya must first renounce
international terrorism. Gadhafi has said his country does not
practice terrorism.
   In his remarks to JANA Sunday, Gadhafi also said Libya ``will
invite American and Soviet companies to explore for oil and gas as
there are massive quantities of these raw materials in Great
Jamahiriya (Libya) and perhaps these companies will even participate
in water projects.''
   There have been reports in recent months that Libya is trying to
induce Americans to return to its oil operations.
   In his final weeks in office, Reagan authorized American oil
companies to resume operations in the North African country through
foreign subsidiaries. He had forbidden them from working there three
years earlier under sanctions imposed on Libya.
</TEXT>
