<FIRST>r a AM-RockyFlats-Water     06-11 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rocky Flats-Water,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Orders Halt to Town's Planned Diversion of Rocky Flats Water</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BROOMFIELD, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency
ordered the city to stop digging a ditch to divert water coming from
the Rocky Flats nuclear weapons plant, despite allegations that the
plant dumped hazardous chemicals.
   Officials of the suburb northwest of Denver ordered the ditch dug
Saturday, citing federal allegations that the plant had dumped
hazardous chemicals into Walnut Creek, which is used for some of the
city's drinking water.
   The allegations were made public last week in an affidavit which
also charged that hazardous wastes were illegally burned at the
plant.
   The proposed one-mile diversion would take Walnut Creek water
around Great Western Reservoir, where city drinking water is stored,
and reconnect with Walnut Creek's outflow from the reservoir.
   The EPA told Broomfield officials such a diversion would be
illegal because the city of 27,600 residents does not have a federal
permit from the Army Corps of Engineers. The permit is required to
divert any river or stream, EPA regional director Jim Scherer said.
   ``Broomfield asked why the Department of Energy can be in
violation of the law and it can't,'' Scherer said.
   ``I told them two wrongs don't make a right. They agreed to talk
with our people on Monday.''
   City officials said they intended to go ahead with ditch, which
will cost about $50,000, but they agreed not to divert any water
into it without a permit, said Marvin Thurber, city public works
director.
   Only a few yards had been dug on the ditch before the EPA told
them to stop.
</TEXT>
