<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-89 2259EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Egypt     06-11 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Egypt,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Egyptian Cabinet Minister Makes First Visit to Israel in Two Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With AM-Israel ^By ARIEH O'SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first Egyptian Cabinet minister to visit
Israel in nearly two years met Sunday with Israeli officials and
said any Middle East peace plan must consider ``the legitimate
rights'' of the Palestinian people.
   Butros Ghali, minister of state for foreign affairs, was greeted
at Ben Gurion Airport by Foreign Minister Moshe Arens who said he
hoped to gain Egyptian support for Israel's peace plan.
   Ghali, who will spend two days in Israel, met later with Finance
Minister Shimon Peres, leader of the socialist Labor Party.
   Ghali's visit indicated a new effort to improve Israeli-Egyptian
relations that have been cool since the beginning of the Palestinian
uprising in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip in
December 1987.
   The last Egyptian Cabinet minister to visit Israel was Foreign
Minister Esmat Abdel-Meguid in July 1987.
   Ghali also met Sunday with a Palestinian activist who supports
the Palestine Liberation Organization and is opposed to the Israeli
peace proposal for Arab elections in the occupied territories
followed by limited autonomy.
   At a dinner given by Arens, Ghali said a comprehensive peace
``must take into consideration the legitimate rights, the national
rights, of the Palestinian people.''
   Speaking before Ghali, Arens said Egypt was an important factor
in the Israeli plan.
   ``The peace initiative specifically provides for a very important
role for Egypt,'' he said.
   Egypt is the only Arab nation that has signed a peace treaty with
Israel _ the Camp David accords in 1979.
   Israel has urged Egypt to encourage other Arab countries to join
the peace plan proposed by Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir. Egypt,
however, supports an international conference on Middle East peace
that would include the United States and Soviet Union.
   In an unscheduled move Sunday, Ghali met briefly with Faisal
Husseini, a Palestinian politician who heads a study center in East
Jerusalem and supports the Palestine Liberation Oranization.
   Husseini said after the talks at Jerusalem's King David Hotel
that ``the Egyptian position, I believe, supports the Palestinian
position.'' He declined further comment.
   Shamir's peace plan is for elections in the occupied territories
to select Palestinians who would negotiate with Israel on a type of
autonomy.
   The PLO has rejected the plan, saying it ignores Palestinian
aspirations for an independent state. Israel bars negotiations with
the PLO, saying it is a terrorist organization dedicated to the
destruction of the Jewish state.
   Ghali is scheduled to meet with a group of Palestinian leaders
Monday and then hold talks with Shamir.
   Ghali said he will deliver a message to Shamir from Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak.
   News reports have said Israel is seeking a summit meeting with
Mubarak. The last Israeli-Egyptian summit was in September 1986.
</TEXT>
