<SECOND>AM-Dukakis-Jackson,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jackson, Dukakis March Together Against Drugs</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson and Gov. Michael S. Dukakis
marched together in an anti-drug parade and rally that drew
thousands of people Sunday.
   The two former Democratic presidential candidates exchanged only
a few civilities before Jackson addressed the rally in City Hall
Plaza, urging residents to drive drug-pushing ``terrorists'' out of
their neighborhoods.
   ``We don't need no police to drive drug pushers out. We must
drive them out,'' Jackson told several thousand people who attended
the rally, dubbed Boston Against Drugs or BAD.
   Jackson was criticized last week for accepting a $15,000 fee for
the appearance. He said he did not request the money, which came
from business sponsors of the anti-drug effort and was offered to
him by city officials.
   Jackson said the money would go to his political organization,
the Rainbow Coalition, rather than into his own pocket.
   ``Oliver North gets $25,000 for his own personal
aggrandizement,'' Jackson said, referring to speeches given by the
former National Security Council staffer. ``It's perfectly
reasonable (to accept the $15,000 fee) and it's a proper thing to
do. It came from people who can afford it.''
   Before the rally, Jackson and Dukakis briefly marched together in
a parade through the city.
   The meeting was one of the first since between Jackson and
Dukakis since the governor's presidential bid fell short in
November. Aides said they shook hands and said hello cordially but
did not have time for any substantive discussions.
</TEXT>
