<FIRST>r f AM-AppleCommission     06-11 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Apple Commission,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Apple Commission Rejects Call for Labeling Alar-Treated Apples</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WENATCHEE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Washington Apple Commission has
rejected a call to put special labels on boxes of Alar-treated
apples.
   Commissioners voted instead Friday to ask growers to approve an
emergency assessment of 25 cents a box to pay for additional
advertising to move the remaining 1988 crop.
   Some 12 million boxes of Washington apples are in storage now,
about 4.5 million more than last year. To sell that inventory before
the 1989 crop arrives will require moving about 682,000 boxes of
apples a week, executive director Tom Hale said. That compares to
the past two summers' average of 425,000 boxes a week, he said.
   The emergency assessment must be ratified by growers, and then
come back to the commission for final approval. It would be in
effect only between July 1 and Aug. 30.
   The manufacturer of Alar, Uniroyal Chemical Co., announced June 2
it was taking the substance off the U.S. market immediately to help
rebuild consumer confidence.
   Alar is the marketing name for daminozide, a growth regulator
that enhances the appearance of apples and increases their shelf
life. It was labeled a possible carcinogen by the private Natural
Resources Defense Council in a February report. The Environmental
Protection Agency subsequently announced it plans to ban Alar next
year.
   The commission's advertising money is depleted now, but a
proposed $2 million supplemental advertising program funded by the
assessment would promote apples as a portable summer fruit, and try
to lure customers with sweepstakes and cash prizes.
   The commission had sent a questionnaire to growers, asking, in
part, whether ``All Washington apple cartons should be labeled
`Alar' or `No Alar' for the remainder of the 1988 crop.''
   In the results announced Friday, 689 growers said yes and 734
said no.
   Several commissioners said they thought segregating Alar-treated
apples would be harmful to the industry. They also said it would be
counterproductive to the commission's plan to erase the word
``Alar'' the public's mind.
   The Alar controversy already has cost Washington growers more
than $77 million this year, and nationwide has cost growers more
than $100 million, Hale has said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
