<FIRST>r f AM-Amway-Avon     06-11 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Amway-Avon,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amway President: If He Can't Buy Avon, `We'll Just Beat 'Em'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amway Corp. President Richard DeVos
has taunted Avon Products Inc. for rejecting Amway's recent takeover
bid, telling a company convention crowd that if Amway can't join
them, ``we'll just beat 'em.''
   The thousands of Amway distributors roared in approval Saturday
as DeVos joked the company's new motto may be ``Sponsor An Avon Lady
Today.''
   About 7,500 of Amway's approximately 1 million independent
distributors worldwide attended the two-day annual convention at the
Amway Grand Plaza Hotel.
   The convention, commemorating the 30th anniversary of the
Ada-based company, comes about a month after Amway teamed up with
corporate raider Irwin Jacobs to buy a 10.3 percent stake in Avon. A
week later, Amway offered to buy the New York-based cosmetics
company for $2.1 billion.
   Avon rejected the offer, and in a series of stinging letters to
Amway it described the direct-sales company as ``marked by
zealotry'' and said such a merger ``would destroy Avon's good name.''
   Amway withdrew its offer, calling Avon's rejection hysterical,
irresponsible and vicious.
   ``I don't think we'll have to buy Avon, we'll just beat 'em,''
DeVos said.
   After an inspired, evangelical-oriented speech about how Amway
distributors are ``life-enrichers,'' DeVos said of the Avon bid,
``We were only trying to enrich their lives.''
   DeVos, with company Chairman Jay Van Andel, founded the company
in 1959 by mixing laundry suds in their basement.
   ``Instead of seeing what kind of dirt they could dig up, we could
have shown them how to clean up,'' DeVos said of Avon.
   The ``dirt'' refers to an investigation Avon launched into Amway
operations to fend off the bid. It turned up possible financial
wrongdoings by the company's chief executive officer, William W.
Nicholson.
   Amway also is under investigation by the Federal Trade Commission
and Securities and Exchange Commission for alleged illegal stock
activity in the Amway-Jacobs partnership.
   DeVos reiterated his support of Nicholson, who orchestrated the
takeover bid.
   The convention also featured two floors of Amway product
exhibitions, while singer Paul Anka crooned for a standing-room-only
audience of distributors. In beginning his famous ``My Way,'' Anka
took out a sheet of paper on which he had penned new lines to the
song.
   ``How could you flop, when we can shop and not go shopping,'' he
sang, ending with, ``You do it Amway.'' The audience responded with
a standing ovation.
   The privately held company, known for its patriotic, pep-rally
style, reported $1.8 billion in sales in the last fiscal year. Avon
lost $404.5 million in 1988 on revenue of $3.06 billion.
   Amway has distributors in about 40 countries and territories,
selling 300 household and personal care items under the company name
and 4,000 brand name products.
</TEXT>
