<FIRST>r f BC-AutoIncentives     06-11 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Auto Incentives,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler Drops Interest-Free Financing For Many Cars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Analysts say a decision by Chrysler Corp. to drop
2-month-old interest-free financing on most models may be a sign the
No. 3 automaker will adopt other incentive programs.
   Chrysler on Friday altered the incentive package by offering cash
rebates ranging from $500 to $2,000 and interest rates as low as 2.9
percent for the bulk of its car and truck line. The program runs
indefinitely.
   Chrysler's move brings it closer to incentive programs at Ford
Motor Co. and General Motors Corp.
   Jeannette Garretty of the Bank of America in San Francisco said
the move could indicate other incentives are planned.
   ``The issue that is facing all of the manufacturers right now is
with sales not as high or not responding as quickly to the
incentives that have been put out there, the question is what do
they do,'' she said.
   ``Do they have to take them off for a little while in order to be
able to trumpet a whole new this-is-it, end-of-the-year clearance?
There are going to be all sorts of deals.''
   Chrysler began offering interest-free financing on two-year loans
for all of its cars and some of its light trucks on April 3.
Effective Monday, the automaker said, no-interest, two-year loans
would be available only on six cars and trucks.
   During April, about half of the loans written by Chrysler
Financial Corp., the automaker's financing arm, were zero percent,
said spokesman Bob Heath. Figures for May are not yet available, he
said.
   Chrysler's car sales were down 2.9 percent and truck sales were
up 5.5 percent in April compared with April 1988.
   Typically, less than 25 percent of the automobile buyers going
through financing arms of the Big Three automakers choose two-year
loans. Garretty speculated that most Chrysler buyers who chose
two-year loans already were in the car market, and were ready with
large down payments.
</TEXT>
