<FIRST>r f AM-Tyson-ConAgra     06-11 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tyson-ConAgra,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tyson, ConAgra Officials Offer Details of Settlement Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tyson Foods Inc. had agreed to pay ConAgra
Inc. $50 million to back out of a deal with chicken processor Holly
Farms Corp., a Tyson official says.
   According to Jim Blair, chief counsel for Tyson, his Springdale,
Ark.-based company and Omaha-based ConAgra agreed to the deal on May
18, the day before the deadline for Holly Farms' latest auction for
itself.
   However, the morning of May 19, Blair said, ConAgra ``totally
welshed on the deal'' by asking for a $25 million deposit that Tyson
would have forfeited if Tyson had failed in its bid to acquire Holly
Farms, of Memphis, Tenn.
   The deal having failed, ConAgra increased its bid for Holly Farms
to $70 a share later on May 19, a bid which the Holly Farms board
subsequently accepted and which Tyson, the nation's largest poultry
processor, has challenged in court.
   Blair said Friday in a telephone interview that Tyson had agreed,
after extensive negotiations with ConAgra, that ``if we acquired
Holly we would require Holly to settle with ConAgra by paying
ConAgra $50 million.'' The payment arrangement had been suggested by
ConAgra, a major food processor and agricultural supply company,
Blair said.
   Blair said that when ConAgra sought the $25 million deposit on
the morning of May 19, it made him so ``dismayed and angry and
irritated'' that he handed over negotiations to an attorney who
represents Tyson in its effort to acquire Holly Farms.
   The attorney's efforts failed to clear the air, Blair said, and
just as the 5 p.m. EDT deadline approached for the Holly Farms
auction, ConAgra began to transmit via a facsimile machine its bid
for the Memphis company.
   The fax transmission was interrupted when Tyson Chairman Don
Tyson called Michael Harper, ConAgra's chairman, to renew talks,
ConAgra spokesman Walt Casey said Friday.
   That effort also collapsed, ``so we turned on the fax machine''
and resubmitted the bid, Casey said.
   After the Holly Farms board accepted ConAgra's $70-a-share bid
over Tyson's $63.50-a-share offer, Tyson petitioned the Delaware
courts for relief in the 8-month-old battle for Holly Farms.
   As part of the proposed settlement between Tyson and ConAgra,
ConAgra would have dropped its insistence on enforcing the asset
lockup agreement Holly Farms granted it in November. The agreement
gives ConAgra the right to buy some of Holly Farms' most valuable
assets in the event ConAgra does not acquire Holly Farms,
effectively blocking any other company from acquiring Holly Farms.
   The lockup agreement is at the heart of Tyson's court claims that
it has never had a fair shot at bidding on Holly Farms.
   The three companies are now waiting for a trial date to be set
for Tyson's challenge to the lockup.
</TEXT>
