<FIRST>r f BC-India-USTrade     06-11 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-India-US Trade,0182</SECOND>
<HEAD>India Will Not Negotiate on U.S. Trade Act</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   India will not negotiate with the United
States over its citation for violating the U.S. Omnibus Trade Act,
under which New Delhi faces retaliatory tariffs for what Washington
calls unfair trade laws, Press Trust of India reported.
   The news agency on Saturday quoted unidentified government
officials as saying that negotiations on trade could not be held
under threat of retaliation.
   Last month, Washington cited India under section 301 of the 1988
trade act for impeding direct foreign investment and closing the
Indian insurance market to foreign companies. The law allows the
United States to impose tariffs of 100 percent on goods from India
if negotiations fail to remove the barriers within 18 months.
   Washington had suggested that negotiations to remove the barriers
begin not later than June 16.
   The United States is India's largest trading partner and two-way
trade between the nations was about $5.7 billion in 1988. India held
a trading surplus of about $700 million dollars.
</TEXT>
