<FIRST>r f BC-Italy-BankIndictment     06-11 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Italy-Bank Indictment,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Head of Italy's Dominant Merchant Bank Indicted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Italian magistrate has charged the head of
Italy's dominant merchant bank, Mediobanca, with deceitful
bookkeeping, newspapers reported Sunday.
   Milan Investigating Magistrate Gherardo Colombo charged Enrico
Cuccia with registering the equivalent of $17 million under a false
heading in Mediobanca's balance sheets during the years 1976-1980.
   Cuccia and other bank officials have said they are innocent of
the charges.
   Investigators did not reveal the alleged destination of the
funds. Newspapers said investigators believed the money was likely
paid under the table to accountants, construction workers or others
performing services for the bank.
   Additionally, the newspapers reported, the money probably was
used to give bank employees bonuses and to improve ailing balances
of some of the bank's client companies.
   Cuccia, an 81-year-old financial wizard, has headed the bank,
which is part state-owned and part private, since it was founded in
1946. He formally retired in 1982 but has stayed on as honorary
president.
   Investigations into the alledged diversion of funds began about
ten years ago and seemed to have reached a halt in 1984, when
prosecutors recommended the case be dismissed.
   Milan magistrates instead continued examining the case and have
issued a summons for the elderly banker and four other people who
were top officials of the bank during the second half of the 1970s.
</TEXT>
