<HEAD>Precede NEW YORK</HEAD>
<HEAD>Kemp Upset By Allegations That Millions Embezzled From HUD</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with Kemp reported upset by allegations,
other details. A version moving on national wire under AM-Robin HUD.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of Housing and Urban Development Jack
Kemp is ``very upset'' by allegations that millions of dollars were
embezzled from the department by private escrow agents, including
claims by a Maryland woman that she siphoned off $5.5 million to
give to the poor, a HUD official said Sunday.
   Kemp ordered HUD Inspector General Paul Adams to conduct an
immediate investigation of alleged embezzlement in HUD's Washington
field office and on Friday Kemp placed four employees on leave
without pay, Frank Keating, HUD's general counsel-designee, said.
   The Washington Post reported the embezzlement losses could reach
$10 million in the Washington office, while The New York Times said
investigations also were under way in HUD offices in Denver,
Houston, New Orleans and Los Angeles about million-dollar diversions.
   In Texas, Reba Louise Lovell has been indicted on charges she
embezzled $2.5 million from the sale of 55 homes in the Dallas area.
   A two-year investigation in the Washington office led to an
inspector general's audit.
   Marilyn Harrell, an escrow agent in Maryland whom federal
investigators have dubbed ``Robin HUD,'' claimed that
extraordinarily lax management allowed her to divert as much as $5.5
million during a four-year period to help feed, clothe and house the
poor in Washington.
   ``I figured that as long as I was going to go to jail anyway, I
would help a few people with the time I had left,'' the 46-year-old
Temple Hills, Md., resident told the Times.
   In a telephone interview with The Associated Press on Sunday,
Keating said that based upon what he has read in the newspapers,
``I'm outraged, and I know the secretary is extremely upset that
acts like this could take place, although as noted all of them
allegedly took place prior to him taking office.''
   Keating would not comment directly on Harrell's allegations.
Attempts to contact Harrell were not successful.
   Keating said Kemp ordered a full investigation by the inspector
general's office and an accounting firm ``to determine the extent of
the problem, suggest remedies and construct a system which will make
this kind of conduct infrequent if not impossible in the future.''
   ``The fact that in Dallas a closing agent could allegedly
embezzle $2 million and not be noticed, the fact that in Maryland a
closing agent could allegedly give $5 million to the poor and not be
noticed shows serious mangement deficiencies, and the secretary
intends to see that that conduct does not recur,'' Keating said.
   The investigation is separate from a congressional inquiry into
allegations that influence-peddling at HUD allowed more than a dozen
former Reagan administration officials to benefit from housing
programs meant for the poor.
   As an escrow agent, Harrell collected money from the sales of
property that had been foreclosed by the Federal Housing
Administration. The properties originally had been purchased with
HUD-guaranteed loans.
   Agents such as Harrell handle the closing on the foreclosures and
turn over the sales proceeds to the government while keeping a small
commission.
   But in 1985, she used some of the HUD money to cover a $37,000
shortfall in her business, Harrell told the Times. When several
months passed without an inquiry from HUD, it became clear to her
the department was so poorly run that it was unable to track the
millions in dollars in payments due from escrow agents, she said.
   She took more money _ as much as $5.5 million, by her estimate _
before anyone noticed. Investigators believe she bought 20 homes and
nearly 40 automobiles for the needy.
   She told the Post in an interview published Sunday that some of
the money may have become ``mingled'' into improvements on her home
that included a swimming pool, a $2,500 wide-screen television and
renovations to her basement.
   But she said she used her home as a homeless shelter and
therefore she could justify the expenses. She said she now has
transferred the home to HUD in an attempt to offset her financial
problems.
   Her scheme began to unravel last year, she said, when a HUD
official in the Washington field office, Everett Rothschild,
detected the diversion.
   Rothschild would not comment when contacted Sunday, but his
attorney, Joseph Scott, was quoted by the Post as saying
Rothschild's suspension was ``an outrage.''
   ``Rothshcild is the person who came in and tried to do something
about this,'' Scott said.
   Rothschild is chief of the property disposition division of the
Washington field office. Keating said Rothschild was placed on leave
without pay along with Margaret White, who heads the office; Robert
Warner, director of housing management; and Charle Womble, a
supervisory loan specialist.
   Harrell faces questioning by a grand jury in Baltimore and says
she is cooperating with investigators trying to track the diverted
funds.
   She told the Times she was relieved her activities finally were
out in the open.
   ``Christians aren't perfect,'' she was quoted as saying.
``They're just forgiven.''
</TEXT>
