<FIRST>r f AM-MellonMemo     06-11 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mellon Memo,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Memo Criticizes Bank's Auto Insurance Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Mellon Bank Corp. attorney warned in a
confidential memo six months ago the bank could be subject to
penalties as a result of some insurance charges imposed on thousands
of auto loan customers in 1987 and 1988.
   Attorney Charles F. Miller said the insurance charges may have
been excessive and even illegal, The Pittsburgh Press, which
recently reviewed a copy of the memo, reported in its Sunday
editions. Miller said penalties could include heavy fines,
forfeiture of interest collected and court-imposed damages.
   The Press said the Dec. 20 memo cautioned that attempts to
correct the problem by refunding money to consumers might result in
class-action lawsuits ``by calling attention to the situation.''
   The insurance charges in question were imposed on an estimated
22,000 Pennsylvania auto loan customers, according to the newspaper.
   The memo was addressed to Paul Mangelsdorf, then an assistant
vice president in charge of indirect lending. He now works for a
bank in Buffalo, N.Y.
   Neither Miller nor Mangelsdorf would comment on the memo, The
Press said. Mellon said in a written response that after
``thoroughly'' exploring the issues raised in the memo, it had
concluded its insurance program is in compliance with all laws and
regulations.
   The Pittsburgh-based bank said it removed two of the charges
cited by Miller from customers' statements earlier this year. The
bank said that action reduced the customers' annual insurance
premium.
   Mellon told The Press it did so because the charges ``did not
offer sufficiently substantial benefits to either our customers or
the bank.''
   The Pennsylvania Insurance Commission has ruled that the type of
insurance referred to by Miller _ collateral protection insurance _
must provide benefits to both consumers and the bank.
   The insurance plan is called ``force-placed'' insurance. Mellon,
like many lenders, requires new car owners to agree to buy physical
damage insurance to protect the bank's collateral, which is the
vehicle. Some banks self-insure on such losses, while others write
off the losses.
   If a consumer allows his private insurance to expire, Mellon
obtains force-placed coverage and adds the insurance premium to the
customer's car loan balance. The interest charged on the premium is
the same as that charged on the auto loan, Mellon said.
   Under this program, a customer's monthly car payment does not
change, so the result is ``a balloon payment'' due when the loan
matures, Miller said. The interest on the premiums also accumulates
until the loan matures.
   John Sinclair, former president of the Mellon Insurance Agency,
said Mellon's program began as a means of cutting high loan losses
but quickly became a money-maker for the bank.
   Mellon lost $884 million in 1987 and $65 million in 1988, but
reported first-quarter profits this year of $77 million.
   Sinclair said he recommended Feb. 7 that Mellon rescind some of
its premium charges and return money to customers. He said he was
fired for insubordination two days later.
   Mellon disputed Sinclair's account of his firing, calling him ``a
disgruntled ex-employee.'' The bank told The Press he was dismissed
for ``appropriate business reasons'' unrelated to ``the product in
question.''
   ``That's nonsense,'' Sinclair replied. ``It was related directly
to the product in question. My position was that if they (the legal
department) deemed the product illegal _ which they did _ it should
have been discontinued.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
